wn   = [[Quer\u00e9taro, Quer\u00e9taro]], [[Mexico]]<ref name = nosoytan/>\n| spouse      = H\u00e9ctor P\u00e9rez Rojano<br>[[Television producer]]\n| children    =\n| parents     =\n| relatives   =\n| television  = [[TV Azteca]]&thinsp;/&thinsp;[[Azteca America]]'s<br>''Deportips Y Mas''<br>''Los Protagonistas''<br>''De Safari''\n| known_for   =\n| nationality = [[Mexico|Mexican]]\n| occupation  =  Television personality, sports reporter, model\n| height      = {{height|ft=5|in=7}}\n| weight      =\n| years_active= 2001\u2013present\n| module      =\n| website     = {{url|inessainz.mx}}\n}}\n{{spanish name 2|Sainz|Gallo}}\n'''In\u00e9s Sainz Gallo de P\u00e9rez''' ({{IPA-es|i\u02c8nes \u02c8sains}}; September 20, 1978)<ref name = reporterclaiming/> is a [[Mexico|Mexican]] journalist hosting the Spanish-language sports interview program ''DxTips'' (or, ''Deportips''); she is also a journalist for [[Azteca Deportes]]. Sainz and her husband,  who reside in Mexico, own the production company that created the show.<ref name = debeines/>  Sainz works in the English language as a boxing match hostess.\n\n== Biography ==\nSainz grew up in a family with three siblings in [[Mexico City, Mexico]], all of them brothers, one her twin. Although Sainz was an athletic tomboy active in a number of sports (she became a [[black belt (martial arts)|black belt]] in [[taekwondo]] at the age of 14, competing in national competitions) Sainz's mother, a homemaker, wanted her to be more feminine, and encouraged her to enter professional modeling,<ref name = \"world'shottest\"/> which she did, shooting commercials for such companies as [[Bacardi]], [[List of companies of Mexico#H|''Hoteles Misi\u00f3n'']], and [[Telcel]].<ref name=solohablaconestrellas>{{cite news|newspaper = [[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]|first = Maru|last = Ruiz de Icaza|date = June 29, 2004|title = In\u00e9s S\u00e1inz s\u00f3lo habla con estrellas|url = http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=35415&tabla=nuestromundo|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100912060543/http://www2.eluniversal.com.mx/pls/impreso/noticia.html?id_nota=35415&tabla=nuestromundo|archivedate = September 12, 2010}}</ref>\n\nSainz graduated with a [[Licentiate (degree)|''licenciatura en derecho'' (\"bachelor in law\")]] degree from the [[Universidad del Valle de Mexico]] in Quer\u00e9taro and a masters in [[tax law]] from the [[Universidad Aut\u00f3noma de Quer\u00e9taro]].<ref name = laperiodistamexicana/> Her father was likewise a lawyer. Additionally, Sainz obtained a graduate degree in sports [[business administration]].<ref name = sainztocover/> Moving from modeling to television sports reporting,<ref name = \"world'shottest\"/> Sainz married Mexican television producer H\u00e9ctor P\u00e9rez Rojano and they have four children, Mar\u00eda In\u00e9s, Eduardo,  Hector, and Maya.<ref name = nosoytan>{{cite news|publisher=La Prensa Honduras|date=April 3, 2009|first=Sabino|last=G\u00e1mez|title=In\u00e9s Sainz: 'No soy tan vanidosa'|trans-title=In\u00e9s Sainz: 'I'm not that vain'|url=http://www.laprensa.hn/Deportes/Ediciones/2009/04/04/Noticias/Ines-Sainz-No-soy-tan-vanidosa|language=Spanish|quote=Est\u00e1 casada con H\u00e9ctor P\u00e9rez Rojado y tiene tres hijos: una ni\u00f1a llamada Mar\u00eda In\u00e9s de cinco a\u00f1os y dos gemelos que nacieron en octubre del a\u00f1o pasado y que los bautiz\u00f3 como H\u00e9ctor y Eduardo P\u00e9rez Sainz. ... Su trabajo no s\u00f3lo se resume en trabajar como conductora con apariciones diarias, sino hacer la producci\u00f3n independiente de Deportips en su propia productora. ... ...El encanto de esta chica nacida en Ciudad de M\u00e9xico, pero criada en Quer\u00e9taro.... (\"She is married to Hector Perez Rojado and has three children: a daughter named Maria Ines of five years and twins born in October last year named Hector and Eduardo Perez Sainz. ... The work entails not only duties as host of Deportips with daily appearances but also as an executive of its independent production. ... ...The charm of this girl native of Mexico City but raised in Queretaro....\")}}</ref><ref name=debeines>{{cite news|url = http://www.elmanana.com.mx/notas.asp?id=103783|title = Debe In\u00e9s Sainz su figura al deporte Mi\u00e9rcoles|date = February 11, 2009|first = Brenda|last = Molina|agency = Agencia Reforma|newspaper = [[El Ma\u00f1ana (Nuevo Laredo)|El Ma\u00f1ana]]|location = [[Nuevo Laredo, Tamaulipas]]|quote = En octubre, la reportera dio a luz a H\u00e9ctor y Eduardo, productos de su segundo embarazo. ... In\u00e9s Sainz se dio a conocer gracias al programa \"Deportips\", el cual se transmiti\u00f3 por primera vez el 20 de septiembre de 2002 y que sigue al aire. Su esposo, H\u00e9ctor P\u00e9rez Rojano, y ella son los productores de dicha emisi\u00f3n. (\"In October, the journalist gave birth to Hector and Eduardo, products of her second pregnancy. ... Ines Sainz debuted thanks to the program Deportips, which first aired on September 20, 2002 and continues to air. Her husband, Hector Perez Rojano, and she are the producers of every episode.\")|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110722224050/http://www.elmanana.com.mx/notas.asp?id=103783|archivedate = July 22, 2011}}</ref><ref name = femalesportsreporter/> Sainz remained an active participant herself in such sports as [[association football|football]], swimming, volleyball, basketball and tennis.<ref name = solohablaconestrellas/><ref name = laperiodistamexicana>{{cite news|date = June 7, 2006|title = In\u00e9s Sainz la periodista mexicana que levant\u00f3 a toda Argentina|url = http://www.sitiosargentina.com.ar/notas/2006/junio/ines-sainz.htm|publisher = Sitios Argentinas Notas & Noticias|quote = Seg\u00fan informa la TV Azteca en su p\u00e1gina de internet, In\u00e9s es 'egresada de la carrera de Leyes por la Universidad del Valle de M\u00e9xico en Quer\u00e9taro, y con una maestr\u00eda en Derecho Fiscal por la Universidad Aut\u00f3noma de Quer\u00e9taro'. Adem\u00e1s da cuenta de que \u201cha entrevistado a algunos de los deportistas m\u00e1s destacados del orbe como Ronaldo, Roberto Carlos, Rivaldo, Zinedine Zidane y Shaquille O`Nelly\u201d. Adem\u00e1s de haber jugado al f\u00fatbol de sal\u00f3n, tambi\u00e9n practic\u00f3 nataci\u00f3n, voley, basquet y tenis. Pero eso no es todo, ya que la actual conductora de 'Deportips' adem\u00e1s es cintur\u00f3n negro de tae-kwan-do. (\"As reported by TV Azteca on its website, Ines was 'a graduate in law from the Universidad del Valle de Mexico in Queretaro and a masters in tax law from the Autonomous University of Quer\u00e9taro.' Also it's realized that 'she has interviewed some of the world's leading athletes such as Ronaldo, Roberto Carlos, Rivaldo, Zinedine Zidane and Shaquille O'Neal.' Besides having played indoor association football and practiced swimming, volleyball, basketball and tennis. But that's not all, because the current host of Deportips is also a black belt in taekwando.\")}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Public image ===\nIn 2010, TV Azteca's website's featured photo galleries of her as well as an article in its \"Bad Girls\" section extolling her as a woman of intelligence and humor, illustrated by a photo of her modeling a swimsuit.<ref>{{cite news|publisher = Associated Press|url = https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5jxB1UjbIt4BBBxEeyWKK7kW33JLAD9I7AM7O0|title = NFL talks to female reporter about Jets behavior|first = Dennis|last = Waszak Jr.|date = September 14, 2010}}</ref> Likewise, during the 2000s, Sainz appeared on the cover of  such Spanish-language magazines as ''Revista Gente y la Actualidad,''<ref>{{cite news|work = Philly.com|url = http://www.philly.com/philly/entertainment/102934814.html?imageId=40281719|title = Inez Sainz on the cover of Gente magazine|accessdate = September 18, 2010}}</ref> ''[[H Para Hombres]],'' [[Maxim (magazine)#Expansion of the Maxim brand|''Maxim'']], and [[Esquire (magazine)|''Esquire Mexico'']].<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.myfoxboston.com/dpps/sports/ines-sainz-mexican-sports-reporter-ny-jets-dpgoha-20100914-fc_9626116|work = MyFoxBoston|date = September 14, 2010|title = Who is Ines Sainz?|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120212130622/http://www.myfoxboston.com/dpps/sports/ines-sainz-mexican-sports-reporter-ny-jets-dpgoha-20100914-fc_9626116|archivedate = February 12, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://guyism.com/2010/05/super-hot-sideline-reporter-ines-sainz-bikinis-it-up-in-esquire-mexico.html|website=Guyism|title=Super hot sideline reporter Ines Sainz bikinis it up in Esquire Mexico|first=DC|last=Scrap|accessdate=September 17, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100918203751/http://guyism.com/2010/05/super-hot-sideline-reporter-ines-sainz-bikinis-it-up-in-esquire-mexico.html|archivedate=September 18, 2010}}</ref> Prior and during the 2010 World Cup, pictures of Sainz were featured on such places as ''[[Bleacher Report]]''<ref>{{cite web|website = [[Bleacher Report]]|url = http://bleacherreport.com/articles/395867-sexy-world-cup-mexico#page/18|date = May 23, 2010|title = World Cup WAGs: Team Mexico|first = Andrew|last = Kearney}}</ref> and the websites run by ''[[Sports Illustrated]]''<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine = [[Sports Illustrated]]|first = Jimmy|last = Traina|url = http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2010/extramustard/hotclicks/06/16/ines-sainz-terrell-owens-incredible-high-jump/index.html|title = T.O.'s up|date = June 16, 2010}}</ref> and ''[[Men's Health (magazine)|Men's Health]].''<ref name=\"world'shottest\">{{cite web|url = http://www.menshealth.com/women-of-mh/models/ines-sainz?page=1#modelpic|title = Is Ines Sainz the World's Hottest Woman?|publisher = [[Men's Health (magazine)|Men's Health]]|work = Women of MH|date = September 17, 2010|access-date = 2010-09-23|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100918093434/http://www.menshealth.com/women-of-mh/models/ines-sainz?page=1#modelpic#modelpic|archive-date = 2010-09-18|url-status = dead}}</ref>  Sainz was chosen by the magazine ''[[FHM]]'' as the fifth sexiest woman sports reporter in the world in August 2009.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[FHM]] Online |url=http://www.fhmonline.com/site/content/article.aspx?id=41540 |title=The Five Sexiest Sports Reporters in the World |date=August 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100811051107/http://www.fhmonline.com/site/content/article.aspx?id=41540 |archivedate=2010-08-11 }}</ref>\n\n=== Sports reporting ===\n[[File:Ines Sainz.jpg|thumb|right|In\u00e9s Sainz at the Mexico vs. North Korea [[international friendly]] [[association football|football]] match in [[Torre\u00f3n, Coahuila]], Mexico, on March 17, 2010.]]\n\nSainz has interviewed, among others, [[tennis]] players [[Roger Federer]] and [[Rafael Nadal]], [[basketball]] players [[Kobe Bryant]] and [[Shaquille O'Neal]], [[baseball]] players [[Derek Jeter]] and [[Alex Rodriguez]] and [[association football]] players [[Ronaldo (Brazilian footballer)|Ronaldo]], [[Roberto Carlos (footballer)|Roberto Carlos]], [[Rivaldo]], [[Zinedine Zidane]], [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] and [[Lionel Messi]].<ref name = laperiodistamexicana/><ref name = femalesportsreporter/><ref>{{Cite news|publisher = [[NBC Sports]]|url = http://outofbounds.nbcsports.com/2010/09/castrodale-8.html.php|title = Castrodale: Ines Sainz shouldn't have to explain herself; it's the men who are acting like idiots|date = September 16, 2010|first = Jelisa|last = Castrodale|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100918035522/http://outofbounds.nbcsports.com/2010/09/castrodale-8.html.php|archivedate = September 18, 2010}}</ref> By July 2006, Sainz had covered three [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] tournaments and four [[NBA Finals]], the [[2004 Athens Olympics]] and the [[2006 World Cup]].<ref name = bella>{{cite news|title = A In\u00e9s, ser bella le da privilegios|date = July 11, 2006|newspaper = [[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]|url = http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/estilos/49298.html}}</ref> As of 2009, Sainz had covered six Super Bowls,<ref>{{cite news|newspaper = [[San Francisco Examiner]]|agency = Associated Press|url = http://www.sfexaminer.com/sports/Super_Bowl_media_day_a_true_circus.html|title = Super Bowl media day a true circus|date = January 28, 2009|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110616142120/http://www.sfexaminer.com/sports/Super_Bowl_media_day_a_true_circus.html|archivedate = June 16, 2011}}</ref> the first, [[Super Bowl XXXVI]] in 2002.<ref name = 60seconds>{{cite news|url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_8163/is_20070131/ai_n51949013/|date = January 31, 2007|newspaper = [[Palm Beach Post]]|title = 60 Seconds with Ines Sainz|first = Tom|last = D'Angelo}}</ref> In January 2009, promoting American football stars to a Mexican audience, Sainz ran an informal biceps competition during the [[Super Bowl XLIII]] \"media day,\" awarding her \"Strongest Right Arm\" award to the [[Arizona Cardinals]]' [[defensive end]] [[Antonio Smith (defensive end)|Antonio Smith]].<ref>{{Cite news|work = AZCentral.com|url = http://www.azcentral.com/sports/cardinals/articles/2009/01/27/20090127spt-sbbickley.html|date = January 27, 2009|title = Bickley: Cards handle media-day blitz well|first = Dan|last = Bickley}}</ref> According to the ''[[Palm Beach Post]],'' at the 2007 Super Bowl's \"media day,\" Sainz was photographed as often as [[Peyton Manning]];<ref name = 60seconds/> and according to ''[[The Daily Telegraph]],'' she was \"besides Manning, the single-most popular person on the premises.\"<ref>{{cite news|newspaper = The Daily Telegraph|title = Colts and Bears fed to hungry 4,000|first = Art|last = Spander|date = February 1, 2007|url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/2307056/Colts-and-Bears-fed-to-hungry-4000.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|magazine = [[Newsweek]]|url = http://www.newsweek.com/2007/01/30/media-day.html|title = Media Day|date = January 30, 2007}}</ref> During a period when [[Terrell Owens]] was not speaking with the press in 2008, it was only Sainz who was able to gain an exclusive interview with the wide receiver.<ref name = reporterclaiming/>\n\nBoxing promotion company [[Top Rank]] hired Sainz to conduct pre-event reports and interviews and offer ringside commentary for the [[Manny Pacquiao vs. Antonio Margarito]] World [[Super Welterweight]] Championship bout in [[Arlington, Texas]] on November 13, 2010.<ref name = sainztocover>{{cite web|url = http://www.proboxing-fans.com/super-sexy-ines-sainz-to-cover-pacquiao-vs-maragarito_101410/|date = October 14, 2010|title = Super Sexy Ines Sainz to Cover Pacquiao vs. Maragarito|work = ProBoxing-Fans.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|newspaper = [[USA Today]]|url = http://content.usatoday.com/communities/gameon/post/2010/10/ines-sainz-manny-pacquiao-fight/1|title = Ines Sainz will be a factor at Manny Pacquiao fight|date = October 14, 2010}}</ref> Sainz co-hosted broadcast commentary for the March 12, 2011 [[Miguel Cotto vs. Ricardo Mayorga]] bout.<ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.nowboxing.com/2011/03/watch-the-cotto-mayorga-weigh-in-live-online/16788/|publisher = NowBoxing.com|title = Watch the Cotto-Mayorga Weigh-in Live Online|date = March 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, it was announced that Sainz would be a host on the [[Netflix]] [[reality show]] ''[[Ultimate Beastmaster]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/digital/news/ultimate-beastmaster-netflix-competition-series-sylvester-stallone-dave-broome-1201769095/|title=Netflix Orders Global Competition Series \u2018Ultimate Beastmaster\u2019 from Sylvester Stallone, Dave Broome|last=Prudon|first=Laura|work=Variety|date=May 9, 2016|accessdate=October 5, 2016}}</ref> Sainz returned as a host for Mexicos second appearance in season 3.\n\n=== Controversy ===\nIn 2010 the TV Azteca reporter sought an interview with then [[NY Jets]] quarterback [[Mark Sanchez]], and she had been standing on the sidelines during practice when Jets players and coaches appeared to throw footballs in her direction. Later, as she waited in the locker room to conduct an interview with Sanchez, she was reportedly the target of lewd comments from players and staff. She tweeted in Spanish: \"I'm so uncomfortable! I'm in the Jets locker room waiting for Mark Sanchez and trying not to look around me.\" And a few moments later, she wrote, \"I want to cover my ears.\" Media persons reported that team members made \"catcalls and rude comments\".<ref name = othersbalked>{{cite news|url = http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2010/09/14/earlyshow/main6864708.shtml|date = September 14, 2010|title = Sainz: Others Balked at Jets' Behavior, Not Me: Says Colleagues Objected, Concluded It Was Wrong; Says She's Been Hassled Before -- Just Never So Rudely|publisher = [[CBS News]]}}</ref> According to Sainz, it was \"the rest of the media start to hear the different kind of things that I didn't hear.\"<ref name = othersbalked/> She accepted a personal apology from Jets owner [[Woody Johnson]] when those incidents became known to him.\n\nIn the immediate aftermath of the incident, Sainz lost a contract to be the spokesperson for a Mexican bank, which she said was \"very painful\" for her;<ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.startribune.com/sports/blogs/107517633.html?elr=KArksi8cyaiUo8cyaiUiD3aPc:_Yyc:aUGE:h4E77U|newspaper = [[Minneapolis Star Tribune]]|title = RandBall Q&A: Reporter Ines Sainz on the Mark Sanchez incident, T.O. and more|first = Michael|last = Rand|date = November 12, 2010}}</ref> however, she said that the publicity resulting from the event also led her to become \"the most popular journalist right now in Mexico and Latin America.\"<ref name = femalesportsreporter>{{cite news|publisher = McClatchy Newspapers|url = http://www.kansascity.com/2010/09/21/2241244/female-sports-reporter-from-mexico.html#ixzz10D2iqv2n|first = Tim|last = Johnson|title = Female sports reporter from Mexico surprised she's focus of much controversy|newspaper = [[Kansas City Star]]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[In\u00e9s G\u00f3mez Mont]]\n* [[Mar\u00eda In\u00e9s|Mar\u00eda In\u00e9s Guerra]]\n* [[Association for Women in Sports Media]]\n* [[Lisa Olson]]\n* [[Jenn Sterger]]\n* [[Katherine Webb]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|In\u00e9s Sainz}}\n* {{official website|http://inessainz.mx}} {{in lang|es}}\n* [http://www.aztecaamerica.com/notas/antesaladeportiva/21434/jets-vs-sainz:-la-polemica-en-los-medios \"Notas Jets VS Sainz: la pol\u00e9mica en los medios\"] &ndash; AztecaAmerica.com\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100918040027/http://www.tvazteca.com/nota/laacademia/ines-sainz-en-la-academia/2009-10-348 Bio at TV Azteca]\n* [http://www.sportsgrid.com/nfl/ines-sainz-shares-her-story-with-cnns-rick-sanchez/ Ines Sainz Shares Her Story With CNN\u2019s Rick Sanchez (Video)] &ndash; ''Sports Grid''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100923212139/http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/columnas/vi_86026.html \"Por los estadios del mundo\"] by In\u00e9s Sainz, ''[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]],'' September 18, 2010\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150402114128/http://thecelebritycafe.com/feature/interview-ines-sainz-01-07-2011 \"Interview with Ines Sainz: The Mexican Journalist Is Ready to Make Her Mark on American Audiences\"], by Tiffany Lew &ndash; ''The Celebrity Cafe''\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sainz, Ines}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Association football commentators]]\n[[Category:Infotainers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mexican entertainers]]\n[[Category:Mexican female models]]\n[[Category:Mexican television journalists]]\n[[Category:Mexican television presenters]]\n[[Category:Mexican Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:People from Quer\u00e9taro City]]\n[[Category:TV Azteca]]\n[[Category:Women sports announcers]]\n[[Category:Twin people from Mexico]]\n[[Category:Women television journalists]]\n[[Category:Women television presenters]]\n", "name_user": "Nardog", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:fixingSpanish IPAperdiscussion", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In%C3%A9s_Sainz"}
{"title_page": "Children of Llullaillaco", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n{{TOC right}}<!--[[File:Momias de Llullaillaco en la Provincia de Salta (Argentina).jpg|thumb|upright|''La doncella'' (\"The maiden\"), the oldest of the three mummies.]]-->\nThe '''Children of Llullaillaco'''<ref name=\"National Commission\" /> ({{IPA-es|(\u025f)\u029du\u029daj\u02c8\u029dako|lang}}), also known as the '''Mummies of Llullaillaco''', are three [[Inca]] child [[mummy|mummies]] discovered on 16 March 1999 by [[Johan Reinhard]] and his [[archaeology|archaeological]] team near the summit of [[Llullaillaco]], a {{convert|6739|m|ft|abbr=on}} [[stratovolcano]]<ref name=\"GVP\">{{Cite GVP|vn=355110|name=Llullaillaco}}</ref> on the [[Argentina]]\u2013[[Chile]] border. The children were [[human sacrifice|sacrificed]] in an Inca religious ritual that took place around the year 1500. In this ritual, the three children were drugged<ref>{{cite web|title=Inca Child Sacrifice Victims Were Drugged|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2013/07/130729-inca-mummy-maiden-sacrifice-coca-alcohol-drug-mountain-andes-children/|accessdate=31 August 2017|date=29 July 2013}}</ref>, then placed inside a small chamber {{convert|1.5|m|ft}} beneath the ground, where they were left to die.<ref>{{cite web|title=Final Moments of Incan Child Mummies' Lives Revealed|url=https://www.livescience.com/38504-incan-child-mummies-lives-revealed.html|website=Live Science|accessdate=31 August 2017}}</ref> According to Reinhard, the mummies \"appear to be the best preserved Inca mummies ever found\", and other archaeologists have expressed the same opinion, calling them among the best preserved mummies in the world.<ref name=\"Washington Post\">{{cite journal|last=Sawyer|first=Kathy|title=Mummies of Inca Children Unearthed|journal=Washington Post|date=7 April 1999|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/national/daily/april99/mummies07.htm|accessdate=21 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Nature World News\">{{cite news|last1=Alface|first1=Isabel|title=Secret Last Moments of 500-Year-Old Inca Mummified Children Revealed|url=http://www.natureworldnews.com/articles/3224/20130729/secret-last-moments-500-year-old-inca-mummified-children-revealed-drugged-freeze-to-death.htm|accessdate=16 March 2016|work=Nature World News|date=29 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Morelle|first1=Rebecca|title=Inca mummies: Child sacrifice victims fed drugs and alcohol|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-23496345|accessdate=16 March 2016|work=BBC News|date=30 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 June 2001, Argentina's National Commission of Museums, Monuments, and Historic Places declared the Children of Llullaillaco to be National Historic Property of Argentina.<ref name=\"National Commission\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.monumentosysitios.gov.ar/ficha.php?idMonumento=839|title=Las tres momias denominadas \"Los Ni\u00f1os del Llullaillaco\"|publisher=Comisi\u00f3n Nacional de Monumentos, de Lugares y de Bienes Hist\u00f3ricos|language=es|date=2 December 2013|access-date=28 August 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203235540/http://www.monumentosysitios.gov.ar/ficha.php?idMonumento=839|archivedate=3 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Since 2007, the mummies have been on exhibition in the Museum of High Altitude Archaeology in the Argentine city of [[Salta]].\n\n==Background==\n\n[[File:Inca-expansion.png|thumb|left|80%|A map of Inca Empire expansion in the 15th and 16th centuries.]]\nThe [[Inca Empire]] ([[Quechua language|Quechua]]: ''Tawantinsuyu'', \"The Four Regions\"), was the largest empire in [[pre-Columbian America]],<ref name=\"SchwartzNichols2010\">{{cite book|first1=Glenn M. |last1=Schwartz |first2=John J. |last2= Nichols |title=After Collapse: The Regeneration of Complex Societies |url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=_gsFrnn9RzQC}}|date=15 August 2010 |publisher=University of Arizona Press |isbn=978-0-8165-2936-0}}</ref> and possibly the largest empire in the world during the early 16th century.<ref>Moseley, Michael E. (2001), ''The Incas and their Ancestors'', London: Thames and Hudson, p. 7.</ref> The empire arose in the area around the city of [[Cusco]], high in the [[Andes Mountains]] in modern-day [[Peru]], in the 13th century. The Inca civilisation did not expand much geographically until the mid-15th century. However, starting under the rule of [[Pachacuti]] in 1438, the Inca swept throughout South America along the Andes mountains, conquering local peoples along the way and consolidating a massive land empire within the span of less than a century. <!--The area that is now northern and central Chile, and north-western Argentina, was conquered and incorporated into the [[Inca Empire]] under the reign of [[T\u00fapac Inca Yupanqui]], who ruled as the second [[Sapa Inca]], or Inca emperor, from 1471 to 1493. [[[DO NOT UNCOMMENT THIS UNTIL A DEFINITIVE REFERENCE IS ADDED]]]--> The Inca Empire reached its maximum geographical extent around 1530, and then began a rapid decline culminating in the fall of Cusco in 1533, along with the execution by conquering Spaniards of the emperor [[Atahualpa]].<ref name=\"Inca Timeline\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ancient.eu/timeline/Inca_Civilization/|title=Inca Civilization Timeline|publisher=Ancient History Encyclopedia}}</ref>\n\nChild sacrifice, referred to as ''[[capacocha]]'' or ''qhapaq hucha'', was an important part of the [[Inca religion]] and was often used to commemorate important events, such as the death of a Sapa Inca. Human sacrifice was also used as offering to the gods in times of famine, and as a way of asking for protection. Sacrifice could only occur with the direct approval of the Inca emperor.<ref name=\"Ceruti\">{{Cite journal|last1=Ceruti|first1=Maria|date=5 April 2015|title=Frozen Mummies from Andean Mountaintop Shrines: Bioarchaeology and Ethnohistory of Inca Human Sacrifice|journal=BioMed Research International|volume=2015|pages=439428|doi=10.1155/2015/439428|pmid=26345378|pmc=4543117}}</ref> Children were chosen from all over the sprawling Inca empire, and were picked primarily based on their \"physical perfection\". Children chosen for sacrifice were generally \"sons and daughters of nobles and local rulers\".<ref name=\"Ceruti\" /> They were then taken hundreds or thousands of miles to Cusco, the capital, where they were the subject of important purification rituals. From there, the children were sent to high mountaintops throughout the empire to be sacrificed. According to traditional Inca belief, children who are sacrificed do not truly die, but instead watch over the land from their mountaintop perches, alongside their ancestors.<ref name=\"NY Times\" /> The Inca considered it a great honour to die as a sacrifice.<ref name=\"Malpass2009\">{{cite book|author=Michael A. Malpass|title=Daily Life in the Inca Empire, 2nd Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XGtFCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA98|date=30 April 2009|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-35549-3|page=98}}</ref>\n\nMany other well-preserved mummies, such as [[Mummy Juanita]], have also been found on Andean mountaintops.<ref name=\"Washington Post\" />\n\n==Burial site==\n[[File:Llullaillaco 1.jpg|thumb|right|A view of Llullaillaco]]\n\nLlullaillaco is a [[stratovolcano]] of {{convert|6739|m|feet}},<ref name=\"GVP\" /> in the [[Andes mountains]] on the border between [[Chile]] and [[Argentina]]. The burial site was covered by five feet of earth and rock at the time of discovery.<ref name=\"Washington Post\" /> The site where the mummies were found has been described as \"the world's highest archaeological site\".\n\nLlullaillaco is in the [[Atacama Desert]], the driest non-polar desert on Earth.<ref name=NatGeo_Driest>{{cite magazine |last=Vesilind |first=Priit J. |url=http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/ngm/0308/feature3/ |title=The Driest Place on Earth |date=August 2003 |magazine=National Geographic Magazine |accessdate=28 August 2017}}</ref> The extreme dryness of the air is a major reason for the excellent preservation of the mummies for 500 years.<ref name=\"USA Today\">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2013/08/15/volcan-llullaillaco-mummies/2660113/|work=USA Today|title=Researcher helps unwrap mystery of 3 Incan children|first=Melody|last=Brumble|date=15 August 2013|access-date=9 August 2017}}</ref> Dryness and cold temperatures are both known to significantly reduce the decomposition rate of human remains,<ref name=\"Weather Channel\">{{cite web|url=https://weather.com/science/news/flesh-bone-what-role-weather-plays-body-decomposition-20131031|title=From Flesh to Bone: The Role of Weather in Body Decomposition|website=The Weather Channel|first=Michele|last=Berger|date=31 October 2013|access-date=9 August 2017}}</ref> and the extreme environmental conditions at the summit of Llullaillaco are therefore very conducive to preservation.<ref name=\"National Geographic\" />\n\n==Rediscovery==\n[[File:Chozas dobles.jpg|thumb|upright|Archeological site at the top of Llullaillaco]]\n\nIn 1999, Johan Reinhard and his team of researchers set out into the high Andes to search for Inca ritual sacrifice sites. Three days into their search, Reinhard's team discovered a grave site containing three mummified children: two girls and one boy. Several gold, shell and silver statues, textiles and pottery were also found. The younger girl's body had been struck by lightning after her death, causing burn damage on her body, especially her face and shoulder. The other two mummies were not affected. Statues made of precious metals and textiles were among the many goods found in the graves.<ref name=\"Washington Post\"/><ref name=\"maam\"/>\n\nSeveral times, the expedition came close to failure. After a long acclimatisation process, including a month spent exploring a lower-elevation mountain nearby, the team finally approached close to the summit of Llullaillaco after establishing a series of camps throughout the ascent. Throughout this expedition, the researchers braved severe winds over {{convert|70|mph|m/s}}, and extreme temperatures, at one point reaching {{convert|-40|C|F}}. Furthermore, at their final camp, at an elevation of {{convert|6,600|m|ft}}, a storm broke and lasted for four days.<ref name=\"Global Press Journal\" /> According to Reinhard, the team \"[was] about to give up\" when they spotted an artificial layer in the site that indicated they should continue the investigation. The researchers followed the artificial layer, which eventually led them to the burial of one of the mummies.<ref name=\"Washington Post\" />\n\n==The mummies==\n[[Image:Llullaillaco mummies in Salta city, Argentina.jpg|thumb|La Doncella on display.]]\n[[Image:El Ni\u00f1o, momias de Llullaillaco, Salta.jpg|thumb|El Ni\u00f1o]]\n\nThree mummies were found at the Llullaillaco burial site: ''la doncella'' (the maiden), ''la ni\u00f1a del rayo'' (the lightning girl), and ''el ni\u00f1o'' (the boy). Once at the top of the mountain, they were allowed to fall asleep, and then placed in a small tomb {{convert|1.5|m|ft}} underground, where they were left to die.<ref name=\"Nature World News\" /><ref name=\"National Geographic\">{{Cite web|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2013/07/130729-inca-mummy-maiden-sacrifice-coca-alcohol-drug-mountain-andes-children/|title=Inca Child Sacrifice Victims Were Drugged|last=Handwerk|first=Brian|date=July 29, 2013|access-date=August 8, 2017|publisher=National Geographic}}</ref> Additionally, they were fed a high-protein diet before they were sacrificed.<ref name=\"Sputnik\">{{Cite web|url=https://sputniknews.com/voiceofrussia/news/2013_07_29/Mountain-cold-makes-15-year-old-Incan-girl-a-sleeping-mummy-0981/|publisher=Sputnik News|title=Mountain cold makes 15-year-old Incan girl a 'sleeping mummy'|date=29 July 2013|access-date=9 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809212953/https://sputniknews.com/voiceofrussia/news/2013_07_29/Mountain-cold-makes-15-year-old-Incan-girl-a-sleeping-mummy-0981/|archive-date=9 August 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe mummies were in exceptional condition when found. Reinhard said that the mummies \"appear to be the best preserved Inca mummies ever found\", additionally saying that the arms were perfectly preserved, even down to the individual hairs. The internal organs were still intact, and one of the hearts still contained frozen blood. Because the mummies froze before dehydration could occur, the desiccation and shrivelling of the organs that is typical to exposed human remains never took place.<ref name=\"Washington Post\" />\n\n===''La doncella''===\n\nThe oldest mummy, a girl found to be around the age of fifteen, was dubbed ''la doncella''. She has become widely known as the \"Maiden of Llullaillaco\". A bacterial infection was discovered in her lungs during an examination.<ref>{{cite web|last=Waugh|first=Rob|title=Incan mummy frozen after human sacrifice still has infection in lungs after 500 years \u2013 giving new insight into diseases of the past|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sciencetech/article-2179217/Incan-mummy-frozen-human-sacrifice-infection-lungs--offering-new-insight-diseases-past.html|publisher=Associated Newspapers Ltd|accessdate=8 November 2012|date=2012-07-26}}</ref> She wore a dress with her hair elaborately braided, along with a feather-adorned headdress.<ref name=\"Ancient Origins\" /> DNA testing indicated that the two girls were half sisters, while the boy was not related.<ref name=milner>{{cite book|last=Milner Halls|first=Kelly|title=Mysteries of the Mummy Kids|url=https://archive.org/details/mysteriesofmummy0000hall|url-access=registration|year=2007|publisher=Darby Creek Pub.|location=|isbn=978-1581960594|pages=[https://archive.org/details/mysteriesofmummy0000hall/page/72 72]}}</ref> She died in her sleep, a fate shared with the other children.<ref name=\"maam\">[http://www.maam.org.ar/index.php?lang=2&seccion=expoperm&seccion2=ninos Secretar\u00eda de Cultura de Salta Argentina \u2013 ORIGEN Y MISION]. Museo de Arqueolog\u00eda de Alta Monta\u00f1a de Salta (2007-12-16). Retrieved on 2010-12-14. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080415160138/http://www.maam.org.ar/index.php?lang=2&seccion=expoperm&seccion2=ninos |date=April 15, 2008 }}</ref><ref name= milner /><ref name=\"archaeology\">{{cite web|url=http://news.sciencemag.org/2013/07/llullaillaco-maiden-may-have-been-drugged-sacrificed|author=Wade, Lizzie|title='Llullaillaco Maiden' May Have Been Drugged Before Sacrificed|date=29 July 2013|publisher=Science Magazine}}</ref>\n\nIt is believed that ''La Doncella'' was an ''[[aclla]]'', or Sun Virgin \u2013 she was a virgin, chosen and sanctified at around the age of ten years old, to live with other girls and women who would become royal wives, priestesses, and sacrifices.  The practice of ritual sacrifice in Inca society was intended to ensure health, rich harvests and favourable weather.<ref>Costin, Cathy Lynne (1998), \"Housewives, Chosen Women, Skilled Men: Cloth Production and Social Identity in the Late Prehistoric Andes,\" ''Archeological Papers of the American Anthropological Association,'' vol. 8, No. 1, p. 134.</ref>\n\n===''La ni\u00f1a del rayo''===\n\n''La ni\u00f1a del rayo'' was approximately six years old when she was sacrificed.<ref name= milner/> Her face, one of her ears, and part of her shoulder were damaged by a lightning strike that occurred after her death.<ref name=\"Washington Post\" /> Her head was lifted high, and she was facing toward the south-west. She was wearing a traditional light brown ''acsu'' dress, and her head, along with part of her body, was wrapped in a thick wool blanket. Additionally, her entire body was wrapped in another blanket, this one an embroidered blanket of red and yellow. Her skull appears to have been intentionally elongated.<ref name=Secretaria>{{Cite web|url=http://maam.culturasalta.gov.ar/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=14&Itemid=18|title=Los Ni\u00f1os de Llullaillaco|publisher=Secretar\u00eda de Cultura de Salta Argentina|access-date=9 August 2017|language=Spanish|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706083923/http://maam.culturasalta.gov.ar/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=14&Itemid=18|archivedate=6 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n''La ni\u00f1a del rayo'' appears to have been treated less roughly than ''el ni\u00f1o'', but without the care with which ''la doncella'' was treated.<ref name=\"Live Science\" />\n\n===''El ni\u00f1o''===\n\nThe body of ''el ni\u00f1o'', who was about seven years old when he was sacrificed, had been tightly wrapped, as some of his ribs and pelvis were dislocated. He apparently died under stress, as vomit and blood were found on his clothing. There also appeared to be an infestation of nits in his hair.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/2007/10/02/child-mummies-yield-grim-evidence-214590|title=Child mummies yield 'grim' evidence|newspaper=Metro|date=2 October 2007|location=London|accessdate=13 September 2017}}</ref> He was the only child to be tied up. Lying in the foetal position, he was wearing a gray tunic, a silver bracelet, and leather shoes, and had been wrapped in a red and brown blanket.<ref name=\"Latina Lista\">{{Cite web|url=http://latinalista.com/columns/globalviews/child-mummy-exhibition-generates-controversy-in-argentina|publisher=Latina Lista|title=Child Mummy Exhibition Generates Controversy in Argentina|last=Trevi\u00f1o|first=Marisa|date=20 March 2012|access-date=8 August 2017}}</ref> The skull of ''el ni\u00f1o'' had been slightly elongated, similarly to that of ''la ni\u00f1a del rayo''.<ref name=\"Secretaria\" /> Due to the way in which he was tied up, it is believed that he may have died of suffocation.<ref name=\"Ancient Origins\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ancient-origins.net/news-history-archaeology/peruvian-child-mummy-elongated-skull-undergoes-analysis-002628?nopaging=1|publisher=Ancient Origins|title=Peruvian child mummy with elongated skull undergoes analysis|last=Miller|first=Mark|date=31 January 2015|access-date=9 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n''El ni\u00f1o'' was buried with a collection of small objects, some of them depicting finely dressed men driving caravans of llamas, and others depicting a ritual activity in which men use slingshots to launch cannons into the lagoons at the end of the dry season to hasten the coming of the rains.<ref name=\"Secretaria\" />\n\n==Scientific analysis==\n\nAccording to a biochemical analysis of ''la doncella''<nowiki/>'s hair, the children were drugged with alcohol and coca before the start of the sacrificial ritual. ''La Doncella'' had been drugged by [[coca]] leaves and a [[maize]] beer known as [[chicha]]. Though all three of the sacrifices consumed significant amounts of these substances prior to the ritual, a hair sample analysis shows that ''la doncella'' consumed significantly more coca and alcohol than either ''el ni\u00f1o'' or ''la ni\u00f1a del rayo''.<ref name=\"Live Science\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.livescience.com/38504-incan-child-mummies-lives-revealed.html|publisher=Live Science|title=Final Moments of Incan Child Mummies' Lives Revealed|first=Joseph|last=Castro|date=29 July 2013|access-date=9 August 2017}}</ref> Her hair contained the highest concentration of coca ever found in Andean human remains.<ref name=\"Nature\">{{Cite web|title=Incan child mummies show evidence of sacrificial rituals|url=http://www.nature.com/news/incan-child-mummies-show-evidence-of-sacrificial-rituals-1.13461|publisher=Nature|first=Erika Check|last=Hayden|date=29 July 2013|access-date=28 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Exhibition==\n\nThe mummies remain on display at the {{ill|Museum of High Altitude Archaeology|es|Museo de Arqueolog\u00eda de Alta Monta\u00f1a de Salta}}, a museum dedicated entirely to the display of the mummies, in [[Salta]], Argentina. The area that now contains the city of Salta was a part of the Inca Empire in the late 1400s and early 1500s, before being conquered by Spanish ''[[conquistadores]]'' in the late 1500s. To prevent deterioration, a computer-controlled climate system maintains environmental conditions similar to those on Llullaillaco. If an earthquake or other emergency were to result in the loss of power, the aeroplane of the provincial governor would be used to fly the mummies to another location where they would be able to be \"plugged back in\". The museum opened its doors to the general public in early September 2007.<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/11/science/11mummu.html|last1=Grady|first1=Denise|title=In Argentina, a Museum Unveils a Long-Frozen Maiden|newspaper=New York Times|date=11 September 2011|location=New York|accessdate=13 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the construction of the museum display, the mummies had been safeguarded by the Catholic University of Salta [[:es:Universidad Cat\u00f3lica de Salta|(es)]].<ref name=\"Latina Lista\" /> Developing a way to show the mummies to the public while keeping them perfectly preserved took eight years of research.<ref name=\"NY Times\" />\n\n==Controversy==\nThe mummies have been the subject of controversy, especially with regards to [[indigenous rights]]. The exhumation and display of the bodies is opposed by some indigenous people.<ref name=\"Global Press Journal\">{{cite news|last1=Laens|first1=Ivonne Jeannot|title=Child Mummy Exhibition Generates Controversy in Argentina|url=https://globalpressjournal.com/americas/argentina/child-mummy-exhibition-generates-controversy-in-argentina/|accessdate=1 July 2017|work=Global Press Journal|date=10 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nRogelio Guanuco, the leader of the Indigenous Association of Argentina (AIRA), called the display \"a violation of our loved ones\", saying that \"Llullaillaco continues to be sacred for us. They should never have profaned that sanctuary, and they should not put our children on exhibition as if in a circus.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Go\u00f1i|first1=Uki|title=Protest over child mummies|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2005/sep/21/argentina.mainsection|accessdate=1 July 2017|work=The Guardian|date=21 September 2005}}</ref> Ferm\u00edn Tolaba, chief of the [[Lule people|Lules]], said that the mummies \"should have stayed in their territory\", and that \"now that [the mummies] are already exhumed, [the museum] would have to return them. It is not good that the museum is earning money with that, charging an admission for something that doesn\u2019t belong to it.\"<ref name=\"Latina Lista\" />\n\nThe high Andes region from which the mummies were taken is believed to be home to at least 40 other similar ritual burial sites. However, in order to \"have good relations with the Indian people\", no more mummies will be removed from the area, according to Gabriel Miremont, the designer and director of the Museum of High Altitude Archaeology, which hosts the exhibit displaying the mummies.<ref name=\"NY Times\" /> Other indigenous people supported the research, however. The Third World Congress of the Quechua Language in late 2004 brought together 300 representatives from Andean countries, at its conclusion the congress passed a resolution \"The congress approves supporting investigations of the :Llullaillaco Children (Salta, Argentina) and the diffusion of such investigations for recognizing the greatness and the evolution of our ancestors from their origins to the present day.\" <ref>Reinhard, Johan: ''The Ice Maiden: Inca Mummies, Mountain Gods, and Sacred Sites in the Andes''. National Geographic Society, Washington, D.C., 2005. pp 337-338.</ref>\n\nSome indigenous leaders have additionally expressed concern that they will not receive any of the economic benefits created by the display of the mummies.<ref name=\"MAAM Ethics\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.saltalibre.net/El-MAAM-un-museo-para-el-cadaver.html|title=El MAAM: un museo para el cad\u00e1ver de la \u00e9tica|publisher=Salta Libre|date=22 November 2010|first=Idangel|last=Betancourt|language=es|access-date=28 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{commons|Llullaillaco mummies}}\n* [[Mummy Juanita]]\n* [[\u00d6tzi]]\n* [[Plomo Mummy]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Reinhard, Johan: ''The Ice Maiden: Inca Mummies, Mountain Gods, and Sacred Sites in the Andes''. National Geographic Society, Washington, D.C., 2005.\n* Reinhard, Johan and Ceruti, Mar\u00eda Constanza: \"Inca Rituals and Sacred Mountains: A Study of the World's Highest Archaeological Sites\" Los Angeles: UCLA, 2010.\n* Reinhard, Johan and Ceruti, Mar\u00eda Constanza: ''Investigaciones arqueol\u00f3gicas en el Volc\u00e1n Llullaillaco: Complejo ceremonial incaico de alta monta\u00f1a''. Salta: EUCASA, 2000.\n* Reinhard, Johan and Ceruti, Mar\u00eda Constanza: \"Sacred Mountains, Ceremonial Sites and Human Sacrifice Among the Incas.\" ''Archaeoastronomy'' 19: 1\u201343, 2006.\n* Ceruti, Mar\u00eda Constanza: ''Llullaillaco: Sacrificios y Ofrendas en un Santuario Inca de Alta Monta\u00f1a''. Salta: EUCASA, 2003.\n* Reinhard, Johan: \"Llullaillaco: An Investigation of the World's Highest Archaeological Site.\" ''Latin American Indian Literatures Journal'' 9(1): 31\u201354, 1993.\n* Beorchia, Antonio: \"El cementerio ind\u00edgena del volc\u00e1n Llullaillaco.\" ''Revista del Centro de Investigaciones Arqueol\u00f3gicas de Alta Monta\u00f1a'' 2: 36\u201342, 1975, San Juan.\n* Previgliano, Carlos, Constanza Ceruti, Johan Reinhard, Facundo Arias, and Josefina Gonzalez: \"Radiologic Evaluation of the Llullaillaco Mummies.\" ''American Journal of Roentgenology'' 181: 1473\u20131479, 2003.\n* {{cite journal |last1=Wilson |first1=Andrew |first2=Timothy |last2=Taylor |first3=Constanza |last3=Ceruti |first4=Johan |last4=Reinhard |first5=Jos\u00e9 Antonio |last5=Ch\u00e1vez |first6=Vaughan |last6=Grimes |author7=Wolfram-Meier-Augenstein |first8=Larry |last8=Cartmell |first9=Ben |last9=Stern |first10=Michael |last10=Richards |first11=Michael |last11=Worobey |first12=Ian |last12=Barnes |first13=Thomas |last13=Gilbert |title=Stable isotope and DNA evidence for ritual sequences in Inca child sacrifice |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume=104 |number=42 |pages=16456\u201316461 |year=2007|doi=10.1073/pnas.0704276104 |pmid=17923675 |pmc=2034262 }}\n* [http://www.andeshandbook.org/cerro.asp?codigo=43&id=eng Complete description, history, place name and routes of Llullaillaco in Andeshandbook]\n* [http://www.maam.gob.ar/index1.php Museum of High Mountain Archaeology] {{in lang|es}}\n* {{cite summitpost |id=184475 |name=Llullaillaco}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Llullaillaco, Children of}}\n[[Category:1999 archaeological discoveries]]\n[[Category:Archaeology of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Archaeology of Chile]]\n[[Category:Human remains (archaeological)]]\n[[Category:Human sacrifice]]\n[[Category:Andean mummies]]\n[[Category:Unsolved deaths]]\n[[Category:History of Antofagasta Region]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n{{TOC right}}<!--[[File:Momias de Llullaillaco en la Provincia de Salta (Argentina).jpg|thumb|upright|''La doncella'' (\"The maiden\"), the oldest of the three mummies.]]-->\nThe '''Children of Llullaillaco'''<ref name=\"National Commission\" /> ({{IPA-es|\u025f\u029du\u029daj\u02c8\u029dako|lang}}), also known as the '''Mummies of Llullaillaco''', are three [[Inca]] child [[mummy|mummies]] discovered on 16 March 1999 by [[Johan Reinhard]] and his [[archaeology|archaeological]] team near the summit of [[Llullaillaco]], a {{convert|6739|m|ft|abbr=on}} [[stratovolcano]]<ref name=\"GVP\">{{Cite GVP|vn=355110|name=Llullaillaco}}</ref> on the [[Argentina]]\u2013[[Chile]] border. The children were [[human sacrifice|sacrificed]] in an Inca religious ritual that took place around the year 1500. In this ritual, the three children were drugged<ref>{{cite web|title=Inca Child Sacrifice Victims Were Drugged|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2013/07/130729-inca-mummy-maiden-sacrifice-coca-alcohol-drug-mountain-andes-children/|accessdate=31 August 2017|date=29 July 2013}}</ref>, then placed inside a small chamber {{convert|1.5|m|ft}} beneath the ground, where they were left to die.<ref>{{cite web|title=Final Moments of Incan Child Mummies' Lives Revealed|url=https://www.livescience.com/38504-incan-child-mummies-lives-revealed.html|website=Live Science|accessdate=31 August 2017}}</ref> According to Reinhard, the mummies \"appear to be the best preserved Inca mummies ever found\", and other archaeologists have expressed the same opinion, calling them among the best preserved mummies in the world.<ref name=\"Washington Post\">{{cite journal|last=Sawyer|first=Kathy|title=Mummies of Inca Children Unearthed|journal=Washington Post|date=7 April 1999|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/national/daily/april99/mummies07.htm|accessdate=21 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Nature World News\">{{cite news|last1=Alface|first1=Isabel|title=Secret Last Moments of 500-Year-Old Inca Mummified Children Revealed|url=http://www.natureworldnews.com/articles/3224/20130729/secret-last-moments-500-year-old-inca-mummified-children-revealed-drugged-freeze-to-death.htm|accessdate=16 March 2016|work=Nature World News|date=29 July 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Morelle|first1=Rebecca|title=Inca mummies: Child sacrifice victims fed drugs and alcohol|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-23496345|accessdate=16 March 2016|work=BBC News|date=30 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 June 2001, Argentina's National Commission of Museums, Monuments, and Historic Places declared the Children of Llullaillaco to be National Historic Property of Argentina.<ref name=\"National Commission\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.monumentosysitios.gov.ar/ficha.php?idMonumento=839|title=Las tres momias denominadas \"Los Ni\u00f1os del Llullaillaco\"|publisher=Comisi\u00f3n Nacional de Monumentos, de Lugares y de Bienes Hist\u00f3ricos|language=es|date=2 December 2013|access-date=28 August 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203235540/http://www.monumentosysitios.gov.ar/ficha.php?idMonumento=839|archivedate=3 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Since 2007, the mummies have been on exhibition in the Museum of High Altitude Archaeology in the Argentine city of [[Salta]].\n\n==Background==\n\n[[File:Inca-expansion.png|thumb|left|80%|A map of Inca Empire expansion in the 15th and 16th centuries.]]\nThe [[Inca Empire]] ([[Quechua language|Quechua]]: ''Tawantinsuyu'', \"The Four Regions\"), was the largest empire in [[pre-Columbian America]],<ref name=\"SchwartzNichols2010\">{{cite book|first1=Glenn M. |last1=Schwartz |first2=John J. |last2= Nichols |title=After Collapse: The Regeneration of Complex Societies |url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=_gsFrnn9RzQC}}|date=15 August 2010 |publisher=University of Arizona Press |isbn=978-0-8165-2936-0}}</ref> and possibly the largest empire in the world during the early 16th century.<ref>Moseley, Michael E. (2001), ''The Incas and their Ancestors'', London: Thames and Hudson, p. 7.</ref> The empire arose in the area around the city of [[Cusco]], high in the [[Andes Mountains]] in modern-day [[Peru]], in the 13th century. The Inca civilisation did not expand much geographically until the mid-15th century. However, starting under the rule of [[Pachacuti]] in 1438, the Inca swept throughout South America along the Andes mountains, conquering local peoples along the way and consolidating a massive land empire within the span of less than a century. <!--The area that is now northern and central Chile, and north-western Argentina, was conquered and incorporated into the [[Inca Empire]] under the reign of [[T\u00fapac Inca Yupanqui]], who ruled as the second [[Sapa Inca]], or Inca emperor, from 1471 to 1493. [[[DO NOT UNCOMMENT THIS UNTIL A DEFINITIVE REFERENCE IS ADDED]]]--> The Inca Empire reached its maximum geographical extent around 1530, and then began a rapid decline culminating in the fall of Cusco in 1533, along with the execution by conquering Spaniards of the emperor [[Atahualpa]].<ref name=\"Inca Timeline\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ancient.eu/timeline/Inca_Civilization/|title=Inca Civilization Timeline|publisher=Ancient History Encyclopedia}}</ref>\n\nChild sacrifice, referred to as ''[[capacocha]]'' or ''qhapaq hucha'', was an important part of the [[Inca religion]] and was often used to commemorate important events, such as the death of a Sapa Inca. Human sacrifice was also used as offering to the gods in times of famine, and as a way of asking for protection. Sacrifice could only occur with the direct approval of the Inca emperor.<ref name=\"Ceruti\">{{Cite journal|last1=Ceruti|first1=Maria|date=5 April 2015|title=Frozen Mummies from Andean Mountaintop Shrines: Bioarchaeology and Ethnohistory of Inca Human Sacrifice|journal=BioMed Research International|volume=2015|pages=439428|doi=10.1155/2015/439428|pmid=26345378|pmc=4543117}}</ref> Children were chosen from all over the sprawling Inca empire, and were picked primarily based on their \"physical perfection\". Children chosen for sacrifice were generally \"sons and daughters of nobles and local rulers\".<ref name=\"Ceruti\" /> They were then taken hundreds or thousands of miles to Cusco, the capital, where they were the subject of important purification rituals. From there, the children were sent to high mountaintops throughout the empire to be sacrificed. According to traditional Inca belief, children who are sacrificed do not truly die, but instead watch over the land from their mountaintop perches, alongside their ancestors.<ref name=\"NY Times\" /> The Inca considered it a great honour to die as a sacrifice.<ref name=\"Malpass2009\">{{cite book|author=Michael A. Malpass|title=Daily Life in the Inca Empire, 2nd Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XGtFCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA98|date=30 April 2009|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-35549-3|page=98}}</ref>\n\nMany other well-preserved mummies, such as [[Mummy Juanita]], have also been found on Andean mountaintops.<ref name=\"Washington Post\" />\n\n==Burial site==\n[[File:Llullaillaco 1.jpg|thumb|right|A view of Llullaillaco]]\n\nLlullaillaco is a [[stratovolcano]] of {{convert|6739|m|feet}},<ref name=\"GVP\" /> in the [[Andes mountains]] on the border between [[Chile]] and [[Argentina]]. The burial site was covered by five feet of earth and rock at the time of discovery.<ref name=\"Washington Post\" /> The site where the mummies were found has been described as \"the world's highest archaeological site\".\n\nLlullaillaco is in the [[Atacama Desert]], the driest non-polar desert on Earth.<ref name=NatGeo_Driest>{{cite magazine |last=Vesilind |first=Priit J. |url=http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/ngm/0308/feature3/ |title=The Driest Place on Earth |date=August 2003 |magazine=National Geographic Magazine |accessdate=28 August 2017}}</ref> The extreme dryness of the air is a major reason for the excellent preservation of the mummies for 500 years.<ref name=\"USA Today\">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2013/08/15/volcan-llullaillaco-mummies/2660113/|work=USA Today|title=Researcher helps unwrap mystery of 3 Incan children|first=Melody|last=Brumble|date=15 August 2013|access-date=9 August 2017}}</ref> Dryness and cold temperatures are both known to significantly reduce the decomposition rate of human remains,<ref name=\"Weather Channel\">{{cite web|url=https://weather.com/science/news/flesh-bone-what-role-weather-plays-body-decomposition-20131031|title=From Flesh to Bone: The Role of Weather in Body Decomposition|website=The Weather Channel|first=Michele|last=Berger|date=31 October 2013|access-date=9 August 2017}}</ref> and the extreme environmental conditions at the summit of Llullaillaco are therefore very conducive to preservation.<ref name=\"National Geographic\" />\n\n==Rediscovery==\n[[File:Chozas dobles.jpg|thumb|upright|Archeological site at the top of Llullaillaco]]\n\nIn 1999, Johan Reinhard and his team of researchers set out into the high Andes to search for Inca ritual sacrifice sites. Three days into their search, Reinhard's team discovered a grave site containing three mummified children: two girls and one boy. Several gold, shell and silver statues, textiles and pottery were also found. The younger girl's body had been struck by lightning after her death, causing burn damage on her body, especially her face and shoulder. The other two mummies were not affected. Statues made of precious metals and textiles were among the many goods found in the graves.<ref name=\"Washington Post\"/><ref name=\"maam\"/>\n\nSeveral times, the expedition came close to failure. After a long acclimatisation process, including a month spent exploring a lower-elevation mountain nearby, the team finally approached close to the summit of Llullaillaco after establishing a series of camps throughout the ascent. Throughout this expedition, the researchers braved severe winds over {{convert|70|mph|m/s}}, and extreme temperatures, at one point reaching {{convert|-40|C|F}}. Furthermore, at their final camp, at an elevation of {{convert|6,600|m|ft}}, a storm broke and lasted for four days.<ref name=\"Global Press Journal\" /> According to Reinhard, the team \"[was] about to give up\" when they spotted an artificial layer in the site that indicated they should continue the investigation. The researchers followed the artificial layer, which eventually led them to the burial of one of the mummies.<ref name=\"Washington Post\" />\n\n==The mummies==\n[[Image:Llullaillaco mummies in Salta city, Argentina.jpg|thumb|La Doncella on display.]]\n[[Image:El Ni\u00f1o, momias de Llullaillaco, Salta.jpg|thumb|El Ni\u00f1o]]\n\nThree mummies were found at the Llullaillaco burial site: ''la doncella'' (the maiden), ''la ni\u00f1a del rayo'' (the lightning girl), and ''el ni\u00f1o'' (the boy). Once at the top of the mountain, they were allowed to fall asleep, and then placed in a small tomb {{convert|1.5|m|ft}} underground, where they were left to die.<ref name=\"Nature World News\" /><ref name=\"National Geographic\">{{Cite web|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2013/07/130729-inca-mummy-maiden-sacrifice-coca-alcohol-drug-mountain-andes-children/|title=Inca Child Sacrifice Victims Were Drugged|last=Handwerk|first=Brian|date=July 29, 2013|access-date=August 8, 2017|publisher=National Geographic}}</ref> Additionally, they were fed a high-protein diet before they were sacrificed.<ref name=\"Sputnik\">{{Cite web|url=https://sputniknews.com/voiceofrussia/news/2013_07_29/Mountain-cold-makes-15-year-old-Incan-girl-a-sleeping-mummy-0981/|publisher=Sputnik News|title=Mountain cold makes 15-year-old Incan girl a 'sleeping mummy'|date=29 July 2013|access-date=9 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809212953/https://sputniknews.com/voiceofrussia/news/2013_07_29/Mountain-cold-makes-15-year-old-Incan-girl-a-sleeping-mummy-0981/|archive-date=9 August 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe mummies were in exceptional condition when found. Reinhard said that the mummies \"appear to be the best preserved Inca mummies ever found\", additionally saying that the arms were perfectly preserved, even down to the individual hairs. The internal organs were still intact, and one of the hearts still contained frozen blood. Because the mummies froze before dehydration could occur, the desiccation and shrivelling of the organs that is typical to exposed human remains never took place.<ref name=\"Washington Post\" />\n\n===''La doncella''===\n\nThe oldest mummy, a girl found to be around the age of fifteen, was dubbed ''la doncella''. She has become widely known as the \"Maiden of Llullaillaco\". A bacterial infection was discovered in her lungs during an examination.<ref>{{cite web|last=Waugh|first=Rob|title=Incan mummy frozen after human sacrifice still has infection in lungs after 500 years \u2013 giving new insight into diseases of the past|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sciencetech/article-2179217/Incan-mummy-frozen-human-sacrifice-infection-lungs--offering-new-insight-diseases-past.html|publisher=Associated Newspapers Ltd|accessdate=8 November 2012|date=2012-07-26}}</ref> She wore a dress with her hair elaborately braided, along with a feather-adorned headdress.<ref name=\"Ancient Origins\" /> DNA testing indicated that the two girls were half sisters, while the boy was not related.<ref name=milner>{{cite book|last=Milner Halls|first=Kelly|title=Mysteries of the Mummy Kids|url=https://archive.org/details/mysteriesofmummy0000hall|url-access=registration|year=2007|publisher=Darby Creek Pub.|location=|isbn=978-1581960594|pages=[https://archive.org/details/mysteriesofmummy0000hall/page/72 72]}}</ref> She died in her sleep, a fate shared with the other children.<ref name=\"maam\">[http://www.maam.org.ar/index.php?lang=2&seccion=expoperm&seccion2=ninos Secretar\u00eda de Cultura de Salta Argentina \u2013 ORIGEN Y MISION]. Museo de Arqueolog\u00eda de Alta Monta\u00f1a de Salta (2007-12-16). Retrieved on 2010-12-14. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080415160138/http://www.maam.org.ar/index.php?lang=2&seccion=expoperm&seccion2=ninos |date=April 15, 2008 }}</ref><ref name= milner /><ref name=\"archaeology\">{{cite web|url=http://news.sciencemag.org/2013/07/llullaillaco-maiden-may-have-been-drugged-sacrificed|author=Wade, Lizzie|title='Llullaillaco Maiden' May Have Been Drugged Before Sacrificed|date=29 July 2013|publisher=Science Magazine}}</ref>\n\nIt is believed that ''La Doncella'' was an ''[[aclla]]'', or Sun Virgin \u2013 she was a virgin, chosen and sanctified at around the age of ten years old, to live with other girls and women who would become royal wives, priestesses, and sacrifices.  The practice of ritual sacrifice in Inca society was intended to ensure health, rich harvests and favourable weather.<ref>Costin, Cathy Lynne (1998), \"Housewives, Chosen Women, Skilled Men: Cloth Production and Social Identity in the Late Prehistoric Andes,\" ''Archeological Papers of the American Anthropological Association,'' vol. 8, No. 1, p. 134.</ref>\n\n===''La ni\u00f1a del rayo''===\n\n''La ni\u00f1a del rayo'' was approximately six years old when she was sacrificed.<ref name= milner/> Her face, one of her ears, and part of her shoulder were damaged by a lightning strike that occurred after her death.<ref name=\"Washington Post\" /> Her head was lifted high, and she was facing toward the south-west. She was wearing a traditional light brown ''acsu'' dress, and her head, along with part of her body, was wrapped in a thick wool blanket. Additionally, her entire body was wrapped in another blanket, this one an embroidered blanket of red and yellow. Her skull appears to have been intentionally elongated.<ref name=Secretaria>{{Cite web|url=http://maam.culturasalta.gov.ar/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=14&Itemid=18|title=Los Ni\u00f1os de Llullaillaco|publisher=Secretar\u00eda de Cultura de Salta Argentina|access-date=9 August 2017|language=Spanish|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706083923/http://maam.culturasalta.gov.ar/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=14&Itemid=18|archivedate=6 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n''La ni\u00f1a del rayo'' appears to have been treated less roughly than ''el ni\u00f1o'', but without the care with which ''la doncella'' was treated.<ref name=\"Live Science\" />\n\n===''El ni\u00f1o''===\n\nThe body of ''el ni\u00f1o'', who was about seven years old when he was sacrificed, had been tightly wrapped, as some of his ribs and pelvis were dislocated. He apparently died under stress, as vomit and blood were found on his clothing. There also appeared to be an infestation of nits in his hair.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/2007/10/02/child-mummies-yield-grim-evidence-214590|title=Child mummies yield 'grim' evidence|newspaper=Metro|date=2 October 2007|location=London|accessdate=13 September 2017}}</ref> He was the only child to be tied up. Lying in the foetal position, he was wearing a gray tunic, a silver bracelet, and leather shoes, and had been wrapped in a red and brown blanket.<ref name=\"Latina Lista\">{{Cite web|url=http://latinalista.com/columns/globalviews/child-mummy-exhibition-generates-controversy-in-argentina|publisher=Latina Lista|title=Child Mummy Exhibition Generates Controversy in Argentina|last=Trevi\u00f1o|first=Marisa|date=20 March 2012|access-date=8 August 2017}}</ref> The skull of ''el ni\u00f1o'' had been slightly elongated, similarly to that of ''la ni\u00f1a del rayo''.<ref name=\"Secretaria\" /> Due to the way in which he was tied up, it is believed that he may have died of suffocation.<ref name=\"Ancient Origins\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ancient-origins.net/news-history-archaeology/peruvian-child-mummy-elongated-skull-undergoes-analysis-002628?nopaging=1|publisher=Ancient Origins|title=Peruvian child mummy with elongated skull undergoes analysis|last=Miller|first=Mark|date=31 January 2015|access-date=9 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n''El ni\u00f1o'' was buried with a collection of small objects, some of them depicting finely dressed men driving caravans of llamas, and others depicting a ritual activity in which men use slingshots to launch cannons into the lagoons at the end of the dry season to hasten the coming of the rains.<ref name=\"Secretaria\" />\n\n==Scientific analysis==\n\nAccording to a biochemical analysis of ''la doncella''<nowiki/>'s hair, the children were drugged with alcohol and coca before the start of the sacrificial ritual. ''La Doncella'' had been drugged by [[coca]] leaves and a [[maize]] beer known as [[chicha]]. Though all three of the sacrifices consumed significant amounts of these substances prior to the ritual, a hair sample analysis shows that ''la doncella'' consumed significantly more coca and alcohol than either ''el ni\u00f1o'' or ''la ni\u00f1a del rayo''.<ref name=\"Live Science\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.livescience.com/38504-incan-child-mummies-lives-revealed.html|publisher=Live Science|title=Final Moments of Incan Child Mummies' Lives Revealed|first=Joseph|last=Castro|date=29 July 2013|access-date=9 August 2017}}</ref> Her hair contained the highest concentration of coca ever found in Andean human remains.<ref name=\"Nature\">{{Cite web|title=Incan child mummies show evidence of sacrificial rituals|url=http://www.nature.com/news/incan-child-mummies-show-evidence-of-sacrificial-rituals-1.13461|publisher=Nature|first=Erika Check|last=Hayden|date=29 July 2013|access-date=28 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Exhibition==\n\nThe mummies remain on display at the {{ill|Museum of High Altitude Archaeology|es|Museo de Arqueolog\u00eda de Alta Monta\u00f1a de Salta}}, a museum dedicated entirely to the display of the mummies, in [[Salta]], Argentina. The area that now contains the city of Salta was a part of the Inca Empire in the late 1400s and early 1500s, before being conquered by Spanish ''[[conquistadores]]'' in the late 1500s. To prevent deterioration, a computer-controlled climate system maintains environmental conditions similar to those on Llullaillaco. If an earthquake or other emergency were to result in the loss of power, the aeroplane of the provincial governor would be used to fly the mummies to another location where they would be able to be \"plugged back in\". The museum opened its doors to the general public in early September 2007.<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/11/science/11mummu.html|last1=Grady|first1=Denise|title=In Argentina, a Museum Unveils a Long-Frozen Maiden|newspaper=New York Times|date=11 September 2011|location=New York|accessdate=13 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the construction of the museum display, the mummies had been safeguarded by the Catholic University of Salta [[:es:Universidad Cat\u00f3lica de Salta|(es)]].<ref name=\"Latina Lista\" /> Developing a way to show the mummies to the public while keeping them perfectly preserved took eight years of research.<ref name=\"NY Times\" />\n\n==Controversy==\nThe mummies have been the subject of controversy, especially with regards to [[indigenous rights]]. The exhumation and display of the bodies is opposed by some indigenous people.<ref name=\"Global Press Journal\">{{cite news|last1=Laens|first1=Ivonne Jeannot|title=Child Mummy Exhibition Generates Controversy in Argentina|url=https://globalpressjournal.com/americas/argentina/child-mummy-exhibition-generates-controversy-in-argentina/|accessdate=1 July 2017|work=Global Press Journal|date=10 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nRogelio Guanuco, the leader of the Indigenous Association of Argentina (AIRA), called the display \"a violation of our loved ones\", saying that \"Llullaillaco continues to be sacred for us. They should never have profaned that sanctuary, and they should not put our children on exhibition as if in a circus.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Go\u00f1i|first1=Uki|title=Protest over child mummies|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2005/sep/21/argentina.mainsection|accessdate=1 July 2017|work=The Guardian|date=21 September 2005}}</ref> Ferm\u00edn Tolaba, chief of the [[Lule people|Lules]], said that the mummies \"should have stayed in their territory\", and that \"now that [the mummies] are already exhumed, [the museum] would have to return them. It is not good that the museum is earning money with that, charging an admission for something that doesn\u2019t belong to it.\"<ref name=\"Latina Lista\" />\n\nThe high Andes region from which the mummies were taken is believed to be home to at least 40 other similar ritual burial sites. However, in order to \"have good relations with the Indian people\", no more mummies will be removed from the area, according to Gabriel Miremont, the designer and director of the Museum of High Altitude Archaeology, which hosts the exhibit displaying the mummies.<ref name=\"NY Times\" /> Other indigenous people supported the research, however. The Third World Congress of the Quechua Language in late 2004 brought together 300 representatives from Andean countries, at its conclusion the congress passed a resolution \"The congress approves supporting investigations of the :Llullaillaco Children (Salta, Argentina) and the diffusion of such investigations for recognizing the greatness and the evolution of our ancestors from their origins to the present day.\" <ref>Reinhard, Johan: ''The Ice Maiden: Inca Mummies, Mountain Gods, and Sacred Sites in the Andes''. National Geographic Society, Washington, D.C., 2005. pp 337-338.</ref>\n\nSome indigenous leaders have additionally expressed concern that they will not receive any of the economic benefits created by the display of the mummies.<ref name=\"MAAM Ethics\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.saltalibre.net/El-MAAM-un-museo-para-el-cadaver.html|title=El MAAM: un museo para el cad\u00e1ver de la \u00e9tica|publisher=Salta Libre|date=22 November 2010|first=Idangel|last=Betancourt|language=es|access-date=28 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{commons|Llullaillaco mummies}}\n* [[Mummy Juanita]]\n* [[\u00d6tzi]]\n* [[Plomo Mummy]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Reinhard, Johan: ''The Ice Maiden: Inca Mummies, Mountain Gods, and Sacred Sites in the Andes''. National Geographic Society, Washington, D.C., 2005.\n* Reinhard, Johan and Ceruti, Mar\u00eda Constanza: \"Inca Rituals and Sacred Mountains: A Study of the World's Highest Archaeological Sites\" Los Angeles: UCLA, 2010.\n* Reinhard, Johan and Ceruti, Mar\u00eda Constanza: ''Investigaciones arqueol\u00f3gicas en el Volc\u00e1n Llullaillaco: Complejo ceremonial incaico de alta monta\u00f1a''. Salta: EUCASA, 2000.\n* Reinhard, Johan and Ceruti, Mar\u00eda Constanza: \"Sacred Mountains, Ceremonial Sites and Human Sacrifice Among the Incas.\" ''Archaeoastronomy'' 19: 1\u201343, 2006.\n* Ceruti, Mar\u00eda Constanza: ''Llullaillaco: Sacrificios y Ofrendas en un Santuario Inca de Alta Monta\u00f1a''. Salta: EUCASA, 2003.\n* Reinhard, Johan: \"Llullaillaco: An Investigation of the World's Highest Archaeological Site.\" ''Latin American Indian Literatures Journal'' 9(1): 31\u201354, 1993.\n* Beorchia, Antonio: \"El cementerio ind\u00edgena del volc\u00e1n Llullaillaco.\" ''Revista del Centro de Investigaciones Arqueol\u00f3gicas de Alta Monta\u00f1a'' 2: 36\u201342, 1975, San Juan.\n* Previgliano, Carlos, Constanza Ceruti, Johan Reinhard, Facundo Arias, and Josefina Gonzalez: \"Radiologic Evaluation of the Llullaillaco Mummies.\" ''American Journal of Roentgenology'' 181: 1473\u20131479, 2003.\n* {{cite journal |last1=Wilson |first1=Andrew |first2=Timothy |last2=Taylor |first3=Constanza |last3=Ceruti |first4=Johan |last4=Reinhard |first5=Jos\u00e9 Antonio |last5=Ch\u00e1vez |first6=Vaughan |last6=Grimes |author7=Wolfram-Meier-Augenstein |first8=Larry |last8=Cartmell |first9=Ben |last9=Stern |first10=Michael |last10=Richards |first11=Michael |last11=Worobey |first12=Ian |last12=Barnes |first13=Thomas |last13=Gilbert |title=Stable isotope and DNA evidence for ritual sequences in Inca child sacrifice |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume=104 |number=42 |pages=16456\u201316461 |year=2007|doi=10.1073/pnas.0704276104 |pmid=17923675 |pmc=2034262 }}\n* [http://www.andeshandbook.org/cerro.asp?codigo=43&id=eng Complete description, history, place name and routes of Llullaillaco in Andeshandbook]\n* [http://www.maam.gob.ar/index1.php Museum of High Mountain Archaeology] {{in lang|es}}\n* {{cite summitpost |id=184475 |name=Llullaillaco}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Llullaillaco, Children of}}\n[[Category:1999 archaeological discoveries]]\n[[Category:Archaeology of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Archaeology of Chile]]\n[[Category:Human remains (archaeological)]]\n[[Category:Human sacrifice]]\n[[Category:Andean mummies]]\n[[Category:Unsolved deaths]]\n[[Category:History of Antofagasta Region]]\n", "name_user": "Nardog", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Children_of_Llullaillaco"}
{"title_page": "Prince Charles of Luxembourg", "text_new": "{{Infobox royalty\n|name=Prince Charles\n|image = Charel vu L\u00ebtzebuerg, Foto in slechte staat, Bestanddeelnr 016-0953-2.jpg\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1927|8|7|df=y}}\n|birth_place= [[Berg Castle]], Luxembourg \n|death_date={{Death date and age|1977|7|26|1927|8|7|df=y}}\n|death_place = [[Pistoia]], Italy\n|burial_place   = [[Notre-Dame Cathedral, Luxembourg|Notre-Dame Cathedral]], Luxembourg City, Luxembourg\n|father=[[Prince Felix of Bourbon-Parma]]\n|mother=[[Charlotte, Grand Duchess of Luxembourg]]\n|spouse=[[Joan Dillon|Joan Douglas Dillon]]\n|issue=Princess Charlotte<br>Prince Robert\n|house=[[House of Nassau-Weilburg|Nassau-Weilburg]] {{small|(official)}}<br>[[House of Bourbon-Parma|Bourbon-Parma]] {{small|([[Patrilineality|agnatic]])}}\n| religion = [[Catholicism]]\n}}\n\n'''Prince Charles of Luxembourg, Prince of Bourbon-Parma and Nassau''' (Charles Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Louis Guillaume Marie; 7 August 1927 \u2013 26 July 1977), was a younger son of [[Charlotte, Grand Duchess of Luxembourg|Grand Duchess Charlotte]] and [[Prince Felix of Bourbon-Parma]].<ref name=petit>de Badts de Cugnac, Chantal. [[:fr:Guy Coutant de Saisseval|Coutant de Saisseval, Guy]]. Le Petit Gotha. Nouvelle Imprimerie Laballery. Paris. 2002. pp. 666-668, 667-678 (French) {{ISBN|2-9507974-3-1}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nHe grew up at his mother's court in Luxembourg, completing secondary school in Canada. After World War II he undertook studies in [[Leuven|Louvain]], then at the [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst|Royal Military Academy]] at [[Aldershot]].<ref name=petit/>\n\n==Career==\n\nAfter university, he returned to Luxembourg, where he worked to address national economic and social issues.<ref name=petit/> \n\nHe inherited from his father [[Pianore]], an estate held by the Bourbon-Parma family in Italy.<ref name=petit/>\n\n==Marriage and family==\nHe married at [[St. Edward's]], in [[Sutton Park, Surrey|Sutton Park]], [[Guildford]], [[Surrey]], on 1 March 1967 [[Joan Dillon|Joan Douglas Dillon]], daughter of [[United States Secretary of the Treasury|U.S. Treasury Secretary]] [[C. Douglas Dillon]] and wife Phyllis Chess Ellsworth.<ref name=petit/> As an unprecedented marriage between a prince of Luxembourg's [[reign]]ing family and a commoner, Charles's brother, [[Jean, Grand Duke of Luxembourg|Grand Duke Jean]], issued a decree to authorize  the union as [[Dynasty#Dynasts|dynastic]]  on 16 February 1967.<ref name=ghda>Genealogisches Handbuch des Adels, F\u00fcrstliche H\u00e4user  XVIII. \"Luxembourg\". C.A. Starke Verlag, 2007, pp. 79-80, 83-84, 449-450. (German). {{ISBN|978-3-7980-0841-0}}.</ref><ref name=petit/>\n\n===Children and descendants===\nPrince Charles and his wife Joan Dillon had two children, who are also princes of Luxembourg and Nassau:<ref name=ghda/>\n* Princess Charlotte Phyllis Marie of Luxembourg (b. [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], 15 September 1967), married civilly in [[Mouchy]] on 26 June 1993 and religiously in [[Saint-R\u00e9my-de-Provence]] on 18 September 1993 Marc-Victor [[Cunningham]] (b. [[Harrogate]], 24 September 1965), son of Victor [[Cunningham]] and wife Karen [[Armitage (surname)|Armitage]], and had issue:\n** Charles Douglas Donnall Marie Cunningham (b. [[Rockport, Maine|Rockport]], [[Knox County, Maine|Knox County]], [[Maine]], 8 August 1996)\n** Louis Robert Dominic Marie Cunningham (b. [[London]], 10 March 1998)\n** Donnall Philippe Cunningham (b. 2002)\n* Prince Robert Louis Fran\u00e7ois Marie of Luxembourg (b. [[Fischbach Castle]], 14 August 1968), married in [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]], [[Suffolk County, Massachusetts|Suffolk County]], [[Massachusetts]], on 29 January 1994 Julie Elizabeth [[Houston (disambiguation)|Houston]] [[Ongaro]] (b. [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]], [[Jefferson County, Kentucky|Jefferson County]], [[Kentucky]], 9 June 1966), daughter of urologist and [[Harvard University|Harvard]] professor Dr. Theodore Ongaro and wife Katherine Houston. Their children, being born of a non-dynastically approved marriage, were initially counts and countesses of Nassau, elevated in 2004 to the titles of princes and princesses of Nassau.<ref name=ghda/>\n**Princess Charlotte Katherine Justine Marie of Nassau (b. [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]], [[Suffolk County, Massachusetts|Suffolk County]], [[Massachusetts]], 20 March 1995)\n**Prince Alexandre Th\u00e9odore Charles Marie of Nassau (b. [[Aix-en-Provence]], 18 April 1997)\n**Prince Frederik Henri Douglas Marie of Nassau (b. Aix-en-Provence, 18 March 2002)\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''Prince Charles of Luxembourg'''\n|2= 2. [[Felix of Bourbon-Parma]]\n|3= 3. [[Charlotte, Grand Duchess of Luxembourg]]\n|4= 4. [[Robert I, Duke of Parma]]\n|5= 5. [[Infanta Maria Antonia of Portugal]]\n|6= 6. [[William IV, Grand Duke of Luxembourg]]\n|7= 7. [[Infanta Marie Anne of Portugal]]\n|8= 8. [[Charles III, Duke of Parma]]\n|9= 9. [[Louise Marie Th\u00e9r\u00e8se of France]]\n|10= 10. [[Miguel of Portugal|Michael of Portugal]]\n|11= 11. [[Adelaide of L\u00f6wenstein-Wertheim-Rosenberg]]\n|12= 12. [[Adolphe, Grand Duke of Luxembourg]]\n|13= 13. [[Princess Adelheid-Marie of Anhalt-Dessau]]\n|14= 14. [[Miguel of Portugal|Michael of Portugal]] (= 10)\n|15= 15. [[Adelaide of L\u00f6wenstein-Wertheim-Rosenberg]] (= 11)\n|16= 16. [[Charles II, Duke of Parma]]<br>King of Etruria\n|17= 17. [[Princess Maria Teresa of Savoy]]\n|18= 18. [[Charles Ferdinand, Duke of Berry]]\n|19= 19. [[Caroline Ferdinande Louise, duchesse de Berry|Princess Caroline of the Two Sicilies]]\n|20= 20. [[John VI of Portugal]]\n|21= 21. [[Charlotte of Spain]]\n|22= 22. [[Constantine, Hereditary Prince of L\u00f6wenstein-Wertheim-Rosenberg|Constantine,<br>Hereditary Prince of L\u00f6wenstein-Wertheim-Rosenberg]]\n|23= 23. [[Princess Agnes of Hohenlohe-Langenburg]]\n|24= 24. [[Wilhelm, Duke of Nassau|William, Duke of Nassau]]\n|25= 25. [[Princess Louise of Saxe-Hildburghausen]]\n|26= 26. [[Prince Frederick Augustus of Anhalt-Dessau]]\n|27= 27. [[Princess Marie Luise Charlotte of Hesse-Kassel]]\n|28= 28. [[John VI of Portugal]] (= 20)\n|29= 29. [[Charlotte of Spain]] (= 21)\n|30= 30. [[Constantine, Hereditary Prince of L\u00f6wenstein-Wertheim-Rosenberg|Constantine,<br>Hereditary Prince of L\u00f6wenstein-Wertheim-Rosenberg]] (= 22)\n|31= 31. [[Princess Agnes of Hohenlohe-Langenburg]] (= 23)\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.wargs.com/royal/dillon.html Ancestry of Joan Douglas Dillon]\n\n{{Princes of Luxembourg}}\n{{Princes of Parma}}\n{{Princes of Nassau}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Charles Of Luxembourg, Prince}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:1977 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Colmar-Berg]]\n[[Category:Luxembourgian royalty]]\n[[Category:Luxembourgian princes]]\n[[Category:Members of the Council of State of Luxembourg]]\n[[Category:Princes of Bourbon-Parma]]\n[[Category:House of Nassau-Weilburg]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox royalty\n|name=Prince Charles\n|image = Charel vu L\u00ebtzebuerg, Foto in slechte staat, Bestanddeelnr 016-0953-2.jpg\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1927|8|7|df=y}}\n|birth_place= [[Berg Castle]], Luxembourg \n|death_date={{Death date and age|1977|7|26|1927|8|7|df=y}}\n|death_place = [[Pistoia]], Italy\n|burial_place   = [[Notre-Dame Cathedral, Luxembourg|Notre-Dame Cathedral]], Luxembourg City, Luxembourg\n|father=[[Prince Felix of Bourbon-Parma]]\n|mother=[[Charlotte, Grand Duchess of Luxembourg]]\n|spouse=[[Joan Dillon|Joan Douglas Dillon]]\n|issue=Princess Charlotte<br>Prince Robert\n|house=[[House of Nassau-Weilburg|Nassau-Weilburg]]\n| religion = [[Catholicism]]\n}}\n\n'''Prince Charles of Luxembourg, Prince of Bourbon-Parma and Nassau''' (Charles Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Louis Guillaume Marie; 7 August 1927 \u2013 26 July 1977), was a younger son of [[Charlotte, Grand Duchess of Luxembourg|Grand Duchess Charlotte]] and [[Prince Felix of Bourbon-Parma]].<ref name=petit>de Badts de Cugnac, Chantal. [[:fr:Guy Coutant de Saisseval|Coutant de Saisseval, Guy]]. Le Petit Gotha. Nouvelle Imprimerie Laballery. Paris. 2002. pp. 666-668, 667-678 (French) {{ISBN|2-9507974-3-1}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nHe grew up at his mother's court in Luxembourg, completing secondary school in Canada. After World War II he undertook studies in [[Leuven|Louvain]], then at the [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst|Royal Military Academy]] at [[Aldershot]].<ref name=petit/>\n\n==Career==\n\nAfter university, he returned to Luxembourg, where he worked to address national economic and social issues.<ref name=petit/> \n\nHe inherited from his father [[Pianore]], an estate held by the Bourbon-Parma family in Italy.<ref name=petit/>\n\n==Marriage and family==\nHe married at [[St. Edward's]], in [[Sutton Park, Surrey|Sutton Park]], [[Guildford]], [[Surrey]], on 1 March 1967 [[Joan Dillon|Joan Douglas Dillon]], daughter of [[United States Secretary of the Treasury|U.S. Treasury Secretary]] [[C. Douglas Dillon]] and wife Phyllis Chess Ellsworth.<ref name=petit/> As an unprecedented marriage between a prince of Luxembourg's [[reign]]ing family and a commoner, Charles's brother, [[Jean, Grand Duke of Luxembourg|Grand Duke Jean]], issued a decree to authorize  the union as [[Dynasty#Dynasts|dynastic]]  on 16 February 1967.<ref name=ghda>Genealogisches Handbuch des Adels, F\u00fcrstliche H\u00e4user  XVIII. \"Luxembourg\". C.A. Starke Verlag, 2007, pp. 79-80, 83-84, 449-450. (German). {{ISBN|978-3-7980-0841-0}}.</ref><ref name=petit/>\n\n===Children and descendants===\nPrince Charles and his wife Joan Dillon had two children, who are also princes of Luxembourg and Nassau:<ref name=ghda/>\n* Princess Charlotte Phyllis Marie of Luxembourg (b. [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], 15 September 1967), married civilly in [[Mouchy]] on 26 June 1993 and religiously in [[Saint-R\u00e9my-de-Provence]] on 18 September 1993 Marc-Victor [[Cunningham]] (b. [[Harrogate]], 24 September 1965), son of Victor [[Cunningham]] and wife Karen [[Armitage (surname)|Armitage]], and had issue:\n** Charles Douglas Donnall Marie Cunningham (b. [[Rockport, Maine|Rockport]], [[Knox County, Maine|Knox County]], [[Maine]], 8 August 1996)\n** Louis Robert Dominic Marie Cunningham (b. [[London]], 10 March 1998)\n** Donnall Philippe Cunningham (b. 2002)\n* Prince Robert Louis Fran\u00e7ois Marie of Luxembourg (b. [[Fischbach Castle]], 14 August 1968), married in [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]], [[Suffolk County, Massachusetts|Suffolk County]], [[Massachusetts]], on 29 January 1994 Julie Elizabeth [[Houston (disambiguation)|Houston]] [[Ongaro]] (b. [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]], [[Jefferson County, Kentucky|Jefferson County]], [[Kentucky]], 9 June 1966), daughter of urologist and [[Harvard University|Harvard]] professor Dr. Theodore Ongaro and wife Katherine Houston. Their children, being born of a non-dynastically approved marriage, were initially counts and countesses of Nassau, elevated in 2004 to the titles of princes and princesses of Nassau.<ref name=ghda/>\n**Princess Charlotte Katherine Justine Marie of Nassau (b. [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]], [[Suffolk County, Massachusetts|Suffolk County]], [[Massachusetts]], 20 March 1995)\n**Prince Alexandre Th\u00e9odore Charles Marie of Nassau (b. [[Aix-en-Provence]], 18 April 1997)\n**Prince Frederik Henri Douglas Marie of Nassau (b. Aix-en-Provence, 18 March 2002)\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''Prince Charles of Luxembourg'''\n|2= 2. [[Felix of Bourbon-Parma]]\n|3= 3. [[Charlotte, Grand Duchess of Luxembourg]]\n|4= 4. [[Robert I, Duke of Parma]]\n|5= 5. [[Infanta Maria Antonia of Portugal]]\n|6= 6. [[William IV, Grand Duke of Luxembourg]]\n|7= 7. [[Infanta Marie Anne of Portugal]]\n|8= 8. [[Charles III, Duke of Parma]]\n|9= 9. [[Louise Marie Th\u00e9r\u00e8se of France]]\n|10= 10. [[Miguel of Portugal|Michael of Portugal]]\n|11= 11. [[Adelaide of L\u00f6wenstein-Wertheim-Rosenberg]]\n|12= 12. [[Adolphe, Grand Duke of Luxembourg]]\n|13= 13. [[Princess Adelheid-Marie of Anhalt-Dessau]]\n|14= 14. [[Miguel of Portugal|Michael of Portugal]] (= 10)\n|15= 15. [[Adelaide of L\u00f6wenstein-Wertheim-Rosenberg]] (= 11)\n|16= 16. [[Charles II, Duke of Parma]]<br>King of Etruria\n|17= 17. [[Princess Maria Teresa of Savoy]]\n|18= 18. [[Charles Ferdinand, Duke of Berry]]\n|19= 19. [[Caroline Ferdinande Louise, duchesse de Berry|Princess Caroline of the Two Sicilies]]\n|20= 20. [[John VI of Portugal]]\n|21= 21. [[Charlotte of Spain]]\n|22= 22. [[Constantine, Hereditary Prince of L\u00f6wenstein-Wertheim-Rosenberg|Constantine,<br>Hereditary Prince of L\u00f6wenstein-Wertheim-Rosenberg]]\n|23= 23. [[Princess Agnes of Hohenlohe-Langenburg]]\n|24= 24. [[Wilhelm, Duke of Nassau|William, Duke of Nassau]]\n|25= 25. [[Princess Louise of Saxe-Hildburghausen]]\n|26= 26. [[Prince Frederick Augustus of Anhalt-Dessau]]\n|27= 27. [[Princess Marie Luise Charlotte of Hesse-Kassel]]\n|28= 28. [[John VI of Portugal]] (= 20)\n|29= 29. [[Charlotte of Spain]] (= 21)\n|30= 30. [[Constantine, Hereditary Prince of L\u00f6wenstein-Wertheim-Rosenberg|Constantine,<br>Hereditary Prince of L\u00f6wenstein-Wertheim-Rosenberg]] (= 22)\n|31= 31. [[Princess Agnes of Hohenlohe-Langenburg]] (= 23)\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.wargs.com/royal/dillon.html Ancestry of Joan Douglas Dillon]\n\n{{Princes of Luxembourg}}\n{{Princes of Parma}}\n{{Princes of Nassau}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Charles Of Luxembourg, Prince}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]