{"title_page": "High Point Panthers", "text_new": "{{Infobox college athletics\n| name            = High Point Panthers\n| logo            = High Point Panthers logo.svg\n| logo_width      = 250\n| association     = NCAA\n| university      = [[High Point University]]\n| conference      = [[Big South Conference]]<br>[[Southern Conference]] (men's lacrosse)\n| division        = Division I\n| director        = Dan Hauser \n| location            = [[High Point, North Carolina]]\n| teams           = 16\n| basketballarena = [[Millis Center]]\n| baseballfield   = [[George S. Erath Field at Coy O. Williard Baseball Stadium]]\n| arena2          = Vert Track, Soccer and Lacrosse Stadium (track, soccer, lacrosse)\n| mascot          = Prowler the Panther\n| nickname        = Panthers\n| pageurl         = http://www.highpointpanthers.com/\n}}\n\nThe '''High Point Panthers''' are the 16 varsity athletic teams that represent [[High Point University]] (HPU) in North Carolina, United States. All of HPU's varsity teams compete at the [[NCAA Division I]] level. All sports except men's lacrosse compete in the [[Big South Conference]]. The men's lacrosse team joined the [[Southern Conference]] July 1, 2014. The Panthers joined Division I in 1999, after having been [[NCAA Division II]] and being members of the [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics]] (NAIA) prior to 1992. HPU was a founding member of the North State Conference, which is now the NCAA Division II [[Conference Carolinas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conferencecarolinas.com/archives/northstate/members |title=Conference Carolinas |publisher=Conference Carolinas |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref>\n\nDan Hauser became HPU's athletic director in May 2014. He replaced [[Craig Keilitz]], who held the position from 2008-14. Keilitz replaced Woody Gibson, who had been AD since 1999. HPU's other previous athletic directors include [[Jerry Steele]], who was also basketball coach from 1972\u20132003, and Virgil Yow, who was also a coach. HPU's men's basketball coach is [[Tubby Smith]], who is one of the university's highest-profile alums and led Kentucky to the 1998 NCAA Championship.\n\nHPU's main athletic facilities are the Millis Center (basketball and volleyball), Vert Stadium (track, soccer and lacrosse) and Williard Stadium (baseball). In September 2018, ground broke on the Nido and Mariana Qubein Arena, Conference Center and Hotel. The facility will host men's and women's basketball and seat 4,500 spectators.\n\n==Teams==\nA member of the [[Big South Conference]], High Point sponsors teams in eight men's and eight women's NCAA sanctioned sports:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.highpointpanthers.com/ |title=High Point Panthers |publisher=High Point University/Sidearm Sports |accessdate=9 November 2016}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width 80%;\"\n! Men's Intercollegiate Sports\n! Team Article\n! Head Coach\n!\n! Women's Intercollegiate Sports\n! Team Article\n! Head Coach\n|-\n| [[College Baseball|Baseball]]\n| [[High Point Panthers baseball|Panthers baseball]]\n| [[Craig Cozart]]\n!\n| [[College Basketball|Basketball]]\n| [[High Point Panthers women's basketball|Panthers women's basketball]]\n| Chelsea Banbury\n|-\n|  [[College Basketball|Basketball]] \n| [[High Point Panthers men's basketball|Panthers men's basketball]]\n| [[Tubby Smith]]\n!\n| [[Cross country running|Cross Country]]\n| \n| Remy Tamer\n|-\n|  [[Cross country running|Cross Country]]\n| \n| Mike Esposito\n!\n| [[Golf]] \n| \n| Alexis Bennett\n|-\n| [[Golf]] \n| \n| Brady Gregor\n!\n| [[College lacrosse|Lacrosse]]\n| [[High Point Panthers women's lacrosse|Panthers women's lacrosse]]\n| Lyndsey Boswell\n|-\n|  [[College lacrosse|Lacrosse]] {{refn|group=v|name=Lacrosse|Men's lacrosse competes as an Associate member of the [[Southern Conference]].}}\n| \n| Jon Torpey\n!\n| [[College soccer|Soccer]]\n| [[High Point Panthers women's soccer|Panthers women's soccer]]\n| Brandi Fontaine\n|-\n|  [[College soccer|Soccer]]\n| [[High Point Panthers Men's Soccer|Panthers men's soccer]]\n| Zach Haines\n!\n| [[Track & Field]] ([[Track & Field#Indoor|Indoor]] & [[Track & Field#Outdoor|Outdoor]])\n| \n| Mike Esposito\n|-\n|  [[Track & Field]] ([[Track & Field#Indoor|Indoor]] & [[Track & Field#Outdoor|Outdoor]])\n| \n| Mike Esposito\n!\n| [[Volleyball]]\n| [[High Point Panthers women's volleyball|Panthers women's volleyball]]\n| Ryan Meek\n|}\n;Notes\n{{reflist|group=v}}\n\n=== Men's basketball ===\n{{main|High Point Panthers men's basketball}}\nThe team began varsity play in 1927-28 and was a charter member of the North State Conference (now Conference Carolinas) from 1930-31 through 1996-97, when the school began its transition to NCAA Division I. High Point won 15 regular-season championships and 13 tournament championships while in the North State Conference and participated in the NAIA national tournament in 1939, 1942, 1946, 1951, 1964, 1965, 1969 and 1979. High Point participated in the NCAA Division II Tournament in 1997.\n\nHPU moved up to NCAA Division I in 1999-2000 and joined the [[Big South Conference]]. The Panthers made it to the Big South final in their first year of eligibility in 2002 and also made it to the championship game in 2004. HPU has had two Big South Players of the Year: [[Danny Gathings]] (2003\u201304) and Arizona Reid (2006\u201307, 2007\u201308). Reid is the only player in conference history with over 2,000 points and 1,000 rebounds and was A.P. All-American honorable mention twice. In 2011-12, guard Nick Barbour broke Reid's Division I scoring record, finishing his career with 2,121 points.<ref>The 2,121 points total is derived from the 2,092 career points as cited here: [http://espn.go.com/blog/statsinfo/post/_/id/39192 Wednesday Recap: Hummel turns a corner - Stats & Info Blog - ESPN] plus the 29 total points scored in the two games after playing Campbell, indicated in the game log here: [http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/player/gamelog/_/id/42014/year/2012/nick-barbour Nick Barbour Stats, News, Videos, Highlights, Pictures, Bio - High Point Panthers - ESPN]</ref> Barbour became the second player in team history to lead HPU in scoring four times in a row.<ref name=gamenotes>{{cite web|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/wake/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/2011-12/release/release_20111207aaa_high.pdf|title=High Point University 2011-12 Men's Basketball Game Notes|author=|date=|website=cstv.com}}</ref>\n\nThe team's prominent alumni include current head coach [[Tubby Smith]],<ref name=gamenotes/> former NBA head coach [[Gene Littles]] and former NBA referee Joe Forte. Littles is the program's all-time leading scorer, with 2,398 points from 1965-69.<ref name=gamenotes/> [[George Nostrand]] played at High Point from 1941\u201344 and went on to play in the first NBA game ever in 1946. Along with Cherry, High Point's prominent head coaches have been Virgil Yow (1933\u201345, 1953\u201362), [[J.D. Barnett]] (1971\u201372), [[Jerry Steele]] (1972-2003) and [[Bart Lundy]] (2003\u201309).\n\n=== Women's basketball ===\n{{main|High Point Panthers women's basketball}}\n[[File:Jennifer Hoover Head Coach High Point University.jpg|thumb|Jennifer Hoover, Head Coach, accepting Maggie Dixon Rookie Coach of the Year Award]]\nHigh Point University started women's basketball in 1967-68 and the team is now coached by DeUnna Hendrix (pronounced de-AH-nah), who was hired in May 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://highpointpanthers.com/news/2012/5/18/W-Basketball_0518122128.aspx |title=High Point University Panthers - DeUnna Hendrix named head coach of HPU women's basketball |publisher=Highpointpanthers.com |date=2012-05-18 |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> Hendrix served as assistant coach for one season under [[Jennifer Hoover]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hpe.com/view/full_story/12750280/article-HPU-hires-Hoover# |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-12-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111108092359/http://hpe.com/view/full_story/12750280/article-HPU-hires-Hoover# |archive-date=2011-11-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In Hoover's only season in 2011-12, the team achieved a record of 20\u201313. Her performance earned her the [[Maggie Dixon Award|Maggie Dixon Rookie of the Year award]], presented to a coach with remarkable success in their rookie year as a head coach.<ref name=\"2012 Hoover\"/> Hoover was then hired by her alma mater, Wake Forest, to be head coach in May 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wakeforestsports.com/sports/w-baskbl/spec-rel/050912aaa.html |title=Hall of Famer Jen Hoover Named Wake Forest Head Women's Basketball Coach - The Official Site of Wake Forest Demon Deacon Athletics |publisher=Wakeforestsports.com |date= |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref>\n\nHigh Point won the 1978 AIAW Division II national championship with a 92-88 overtime win over South Carolina State. The following year, High Point set a program record with 33 wins but was unable to defend its national title, falling to Tougaloo in the AIAW Region II Tournament.\n\nHigh Point completed its transition to Division I in 1999-2000 and joined the Big South Conference. High Point has finished above .500 in the Big South in every season since 2000-01. HPU won the Big South regular season championship in 2006-07, the team's only title since joining the league. High Point finished second in the Big South regular season and made it to the Big South tournament final in 2011-12, just the second time the team finished in the top two in the standings and made it to the championship in the same season. High Point earned its second WNIT berth in 2012.\n\nHigh Point\u2019s all-time leading scorer is current Spring Hill College head coach Karen (Curtis) McConico who scored 2,612 points from 1994-98. The team\u2019s most prominent alumnus is former Duke head coach and current television color commentator [[Debbie Leonard]] who played for High Point from 1970-74.<ref>[http://www.theacc.com/legends/wbb/2011/acc-legends-playerpage-Debbie-Leonard.html ]{{dead link|date=September 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe first female player played on a college men's basketball team in 1944 when then High Point men's coach Virgil Yow recruited Nancy Isenhour to be on the team. She started three games.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.journalnow.com/sports/2011/aug/14/wsmet06-yow-coached-championship-teams-with-practi-ar-1297981/ |title=Yow coached championship teams with practice, practice, practice - Winston-Salem Journal: Nation / World |publisher=.journalnow.com |date=2011-08-14 |accessdate=2015-09-21 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130127001803/http://www2.journalnow.com/sports/2011/aug/14/wsmet06-yow-coached-championship-teams-with-practi-ar-1297981/# |archive-date=2013-01-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Cross country and track & field ===\nHead coach Mike Esposito leads HPU's men's and women's cross country, indoor and outdoor track & field teams. Esposito was coach at [[Mount Tabor High School]] in Winston-Salem, North Carolina, for 19 years and has been High Point's head coach since 2005. HPU's longest-tenured coach was Bob Davidson, who led HPU for 39 seasons into the early 2000s. The Panthers' strongest events are cross country and long distance events in track & field. HPU's men's cross country team won three-straight Big South Championships from 2002\u201304 and has been runner-up at the Big South Championship from 2007-11. The women's cross country team won its first Big South Championship in 2011 and Esposito was named conference Coach of the Year. The Panthers have had one NCAA Division I All-American in track & field, Jemissa Hess in the indoor mile in 2005. Two alumni have competed in the Olympics: Taylor Milne represented Canada in the 1,500-meter in 2008 and Tamas Kovacs represented Hungary in the marathon in 2012. Other notable alumni include former Tennessee head coach Bill Webb and current ZAP Fitness runners Jesse Cherry and Cole Atkins. HPU's Vert Stadium is named in honor of Dick Vert, an HPU trustee who was a cross country and middle distance runner and graduated from HPU in 1960.\n\n=== Football ===\nHigh Point University had football from the 1920s until 1950 and was a member of the North State Conference. HPU played at NC State in the 1930 season opener, which was the first night football game played in the state of North Carolina. The team played at Albion Millis Stadium, now the site of Vert Stadium. There is often speculation about High Point restarting a football program but no timeline has been announced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greensborosports.com/2010/09/15/hpu-will-add-football-but-new-arena-for-basketball-and-pharmacy-school-will-come-first-as-part-of-2-1-billion-expansion/ |title=HPU will add football, but new arena for basketball and pharmacy school will come first as part of $2.1 billion expansion |publisher=Greensboro Sports |date=2010-09-15 |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Men's golf ===\nMen's golf is one of High Point's longest-running sports behind men's basketball. The team moved up to NCAA Division I in 1999 and had its best Big South Championship finish, third, in 2006. HPU's highest individual finisher was Ryan Taylor, who placed second in 2007. The team's most prominent alumnus is Roger Watson, who played for HPU from 1963\u201366, won national club championships in 1974 and 1975 and has since been inducted to several halls of fame, including the NAIA Hall of Fame and North Carolina Sports Hall of Fame.<ref>[http://www.ncshof.org/inductees_detail.php?i_recid=286 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101220133934/http://www.ncshof.org/inductees_detail.php?i_recid=286 |date=December 20, 2010 }}</ref> High Point named Brady Gregor head coach in 2016, replacing Greg Flesher (2012\u201316).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://highpointpanthers.com/news/2012/5/25/M-Golf_0525124932.aspx |title=High Point University Panthers - Flesher named head coach of HPU men's golf |publisher=Highpointpanthers.com |date=2012-05-25 |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Women's golf ===\nHigh Point University started women's golf in 2003-04 and the team achieved its highest Big South Championship finish - third - in 2005. HPU has had one individual Big South women's golf champion, Ann Marie Dalton in 2008. Vici Pate Flesher was named head coach in 2010 and led HPU to a fourth-place finish in the 2011 Big South Championship, up from eighth the year before.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://highpointpanthers.com/news/2011/4/13/W-Golf_0413110630.aspx |title=High Point University Panthers - HPU women's golf takes fourth at Big South Championship |publisher=Highpointpanthers.com |date=2011-04-13 |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> Pate Flesher led the [[Methodist University|Methodist College]] women's golf team to seven-straight NCAA Division III championships.\n\n=== Men's lacrosse ===\nHigh Point University announced the addition of men's [[lacrosse]] as part of the university's $2.1 billion growth plan in September 2010. HPU's first varsity men's lacrosse season will be 2013. HPU named Jon Torpey head coach in 2010 and he joined HPU on a full-time basis in June 2011. Torpey's college teammate at Ohio State, Pat Tracy, as well as former Maryland attacker Michael Phipps joined HPU as assistant coaches in 2011. High Point brought in 20 players for the 2011-12 season, who redshirted in preparation for the inaugural varsity season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://highpointpanthers.com/news/2011/8/30/M-Lacrosse_0830111112.aspx |title=High Point University Panthers - High Point men's lacrosse begins individual workouts |publisher=Highpointpanthers.com |date=2011-08-30 |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> The 2012-13 roster features 39 players, including three from North Carolina and three from Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://highpointpanthers.com/roster.aspx?tab=roster2&path=mlacrosse |title=High Point University Panthers - 2016 Men's Lacrosse Roster |publisher=Highpointpanthers.com |date= |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Women's lacrosse ===\n{{main|High Point Panthers women's lacrosse}}\nHigh Point University announced the addition of women's lacrosse in 2009 and won the National Lacrosse Conference championship in its first season of 2011. The Panthers went 15-4 in their inaugural campaign, setting a record for wins by a first-year NCAA Division I program. The previous record was 13-4 by Navy in 2008. The team is coached by Lyndsey Boswell, who was named NLC Coach of the Year in 2011. She had been head coach at St. Andrews Presbyterian College and was an NCAA Division II All-American while playing at Pfeiffer. HPU attacker Grace Gaeng transferred from Maryland and was named NLC Player of the Year in 2011. The team repeated with a 15-4 record in 2012 and won the NLC regular season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://highpointpanthers.com/schedule.aspx?schedule=308&path=wlax |title=High Point University Panthers - 2011-12 Women's Lacrosse Schedule |publisher=Highpointpanthers.com |date= |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> High Point moved to the Big South Conference in 2013 and has won the conference tournament in 2013, 2014, and 2017. In the 2013 NCAA tournament, they lost 18-7 to [[Loyola Greyhounds|Loyola (Maryland)]] and in 2014 they fell 18-4 to [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish|Notre Dame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highpointpanthers.com/documents/2017/3/20/2017_WLAX_Record_Book.pdf|title=High Point University Panthers - 2017 Women's Lacrosse Record Book|author=|date=|website=www.highpointpanthers.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Men's soccer ===\n{{main|High Point Panthers Men's Soccer}}\nHigh Point men's soccer began play in 1929. In their second season in 1930, the Panthers hosted the first-ever intercollegiate soccer game held below the Mason\u2013Dixon line, beating Catawba College 1-0.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://issuu.com/hpenterprise/docs/everythinghp-reduce/75 |title=Everything High Point 2011 by High Point Enterprise |publisher=ISSUU |date= |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> The team was dropped in 1942 due to World War II but was then brought back in 1971 and moved to Division I in 1999.\n\nHPU recorded its best overall record and won its first-ever Big South Regular Season Championship in 2010 when the team went 16-4-1 overall and perfect 8-0-0 in the Big South. The Panthers reached the Big South Championship twice but lost both times, falling to Winthrop in 2006 and Coastal Carolina in 2010. Karo Okiomah became HPU\u2019s first Big South Player of the Year and All-American after scoring 12 goals in 16 games for the Panthers in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.socceramerica.com/article/40731/mens-ncaa-division-i-all-american-team.html |title=Men's NCAA Division I All-American Team 12/11/2010 |publisher=SoccerAmerica |date=2010-12-11 |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> The team achieved national rankings in 2010 and 2012 and is the only HPU team to achieve a Div. I ranking to date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://highpointpanthers.com/news/2012/9/17/M-Soccer_0917123342.aspx?path=msoc |title=High Point University Panthers - Men's soccer ranked 28th by College Soccer News |publisher=Highpointpanthers.com |date= |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> Dustin Fonder was named High Point's head coach in 2007 and was named Big South Coach of the Year in 2009 and 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigsouthsports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=25877&SPID=2024&DB_LANG=C&DB_OEM_ID=4800&ATCLID=205028238 |title=Big South Announces 2010 Men's Soccer Awards |publisher=BigSouthSports.com |date=2010-11-11 |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Women's soccer ===\n{{main|High Point Panthers women's soccer}}\nHigh Point University began women's soccer in 1992 and won Big South Tournaments in 2003, 2007, 2009 and 2010, advancing to the NCAA Tournament each of those seasons. The program holds a Big South record with six-straight shutouts in conference tournament games, not allowing a goal in either the 2009 or 2010 tournaments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigsouthsports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=25860&SPID=2022&DB_LANG=C&DB_OEM_ID=4800&ATCLID=205026569 |title=High Point Wins Big South Women's Soccer Championship |publisher=BigSouthSports.com |date=2010-11-08 |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> HPU tied for its first Big South regular season title in 2010. In its most recent NCAA Tournament game at Maryland on November 12, 2010, High Point led 1\u20130 before falling to the Terrapins, 4\u20131. The team is coached by former Francis Marion head coach Marty Beall.\n\n=== Women's volleyball ===\n{{main|High Point Panthers women's volleyball}}\nHigh Point University began its volleyball program in 1973 and moved up to NCAA Division I in 1999. The Panthers tied for their first Big South regular season championship in 2008, going 26-7 overall and 13-3 in league play. Former Dayton and Maryland assistant coach Jason Oliver was named HPU's head coach in 2009 and led the team to its first-ever Big South Tournament title and NCAA appearance in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://highpointpanthers.com/news/2010/11/20/Volleyball_1120103742.aspx?path=wvball |title=High Point University Panthers - High Point wins first-ever Big South volleyball title |publisher=Highpointpanthers.com |date=2010-11-20 |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> Audie Gonzalez was named tournament MVP. The Panthers played No. 12 Duke, taking a 3-0 loss at Cameron Indoor Stadium in their first NCAA Tournament game on December 3, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://highpointpanthers.com/news/2010/12/3/Volleyball_1203103005.aspx?path=wvball |title=High Point University Panthers - Panthers fall to No. 12 Duke in opening round of NCAA Tourney |publisher=Highpointpanthers.com |date=2010-12-03 |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> In 2016, Tom Mendoza was named head coach, and in his first year, he led High Point to a 23-10 record and another Big South conference title. In the [[2016 NCAA Division I Women's Volleyball Tournament|NCAA tournament]], the Panthers lost to No. 7 North Carolina in three sets.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highpointpanthers.com/news/2016/12/2/volleyball-hpus-postseason-run-ends-in-3-0-setback-at-unc.aspx|title=HPU\u2019s postseason run ends in 3-0 setback at UNC|author=|date=|website=High Point University}}</ref>\n\n=== Men's and Women's Tennis ===\nHigh Point University stopped its tennis program in 2008. Most recently the 2003 Men's team won the Big South Tennis Championship defeating fellow Big South member Winthrop University. The Panthers, who played in five consecutive NAIA national championship tournaments (1970\u201375) finished #4 in 1974 NAIA Men's National Championship in Kansas City, Mo. Coach Ray Alley was named 1975 NAIA men's Tennis National Coach of the Year. Peter Ranney was named NAIA Honorable Mention All-American in 1975.\n\nFinland stars from the early 1990s and 2000s included All-Conference, Rolex Champion, and Athletes of the Year players Vesa Kemppainen, Pekka Pohjamo, and Tavvi Surousa.  High Point star Pekka Pohjamo won the singles and doubles at the 1994 Rolex ITA Collegiate Invitational. He teamed with American Donald Marriott to take the doubles title. Donald Marriott who played in the early 1990s also garnered All-Conference, Millis-Scholar Athlete, and All-District awards. Marriott would also win multiple \"City of High Point\" tennis championships 96,98,03 and North Carolina State Doubles titles including the 2003 NC State Mixed Doubles Championship. He is currently the Men's and Women's Head Tennis coach for Lee's McRae College in Banner Elk, NC.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"2012 Hoover\">{{cite web|title=Jennifer Hoover named the 2012 Spalding Maggie Dixon Division I Rookie Coach of the Year|url=http://www.wbca.org/blog/index.cfm/2012/4/2/Jennifer-Hoover-named-2012-Spalding-Maggie-Dixon-NCAA-DI-Rookie-Coach-of-the-Year/|publisher=WBCA|accessdate=6 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120411123354/http://www.wbca.org/blog/index.cfm/2012/4/2/Jennifer-Hoover-named-2012-Spalding-Maggie-Dixon-NCAA-DI-Rookie-Coach-of-the-Year/#|archive-date=2012-04-11|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.highpointpanthers.com/}}\n\n{{Big South Conference navbox}}\n{{North Carolina Sports}}\n\n[[Category:High Point Panthers| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox college athletics\n| name            = High Point Panthers\n| logo            = High Point Panthers logo.svg\n| logo_width      = 250\n| association     = NCAA\n| university      = [[High Point University]]\n| conference      = [[Big South Conference]]<br>[[Southern Conference]] (men's lacrosse)\n| division        = Division I\n| director        = Dan Hauser \n| location            = [[High Point, North Carolina]]\n| teams           = 16\n| basketballarena = [[Millis Center]]\n| baseballfield   = [[George S. Erath Field at Coy O. Williard Baseball Stadium]]\n| arena2          = Vert Track, Soccer and Lacrosse Stadium (track, soccer, lacrosse)\n| mascot          = Prowler the Panther\n| nickname        = Panthers\n| pageurl         = http://www.highpointpanthers.com/\n}}\n\nThe '''High Point Panthers''' are the 16 varsity athletic teams that represent [[High Point University]] (HPU) in North Carolina, United States. All of HPU's varsity teams compete at the [[NCAA Division I]] level. All sports except men's lacrosse compete in the [[Big South Conference]]. The men's lacrosse team joined the [[Southern Conference]] July 1, 2014. The Panthers joined Division I in 1999, after having been [[NCAA Division II]] and being members of the [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics]] (NAIA) prior to 1992. HPU was a founding member of the North State Conference, which is now the NCAA Division II [[Conference Carolinas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conferencecarolinas.com/archives/northstate/members |title=Conference Carolinas |publisher=Conference Carolinas |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref>\n\nDan Hauser became HPU's athletic director in May 2014. He replaced [[Craig Keilitz]], who held the position from 2008-14. Keilitz replaced Woody Gibson, who had been AD since 1999. HPU's other previous athletic directors include [[Jerry Steele]], who was also basketball coach from 1972\u20132003, and Virgil Yow, who was also a coach. HPU's men's basketball coach is [[Tubby Smith]], who is one of the university's highest-profile alums and led Kentucky to the 1998 NCAA Championship.\n\nHPU's main athletic facilities are the Millis Center (basketball and volleyball), Vert Stadium (track, soccer and lacrosse) and Williard Stadium (baseball). In September 2018, ground broke on the Nido and Mariana Qubein Arena, Conference Center and Hotel. The facility will host men's and women's basketball and seat 4,500 spectators.\n\n==Teams==\nA member of the [[Big South Conference]], High Point sponsors teams in eight men's and eight women's NCAA sanctioned sports:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.highpointpanthers.com/ |title=High Point Panthers |publisher=High Point University/Sidearm Sports |accessdate=9 November 2016}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width 80%;\"\n! Men's Intercollegiate Sports\n! Team Article\n! Head Coach\n!\n! Women's Intercollegiate Sports\n! Team Article\n! Head Coach\n|-\n| [[College Baseball|Baseball]]\n| [[High Point Panthers baseball|Panthers baseball]]\n| [[Craig Cozart]]\n!\n| [[College Basketball|Basketball]]\n| [[High Point Panthers women's basketball|Panthers women's basketball]]\n| DeUnna Hendrix\n|-\n|  [[College Basketball|Basketball]] \n| [[High Point Panthers men's basketball|Panthers men's basketball]]\n| [[Tubby Smith]]\n!\n| [[Cross country running|Cross Country]]\n| \n| Remy Tamer\n|-\n|  [[Cross country running|Cross Country]]\n| \n| Mike Esposito\n!\n| [[Golf]] \n| \n| Alexis Bennett\n|-\n| [[Golf]] \n| \n| Brady Gregor\n!\n| [[College lacrosse|Lacrosse]]\n| [[High Point Panthers women's lacrosse|Panthers women's lacrosse]]\n| Lyndsey Boswell\n|-\n|  [[College lacrosse|Lacrosse]] {{refn|group=v|name=Lacrosse|Men's lacrosse competes as an Associate member of the [[Southern Conference]].}}\n| \n| Jon Torpey\n!\n| [[College soccer|Soccer]]\n| [[High Point Panthers women's soccer|Panthers women's soccer]]\n| Brandi Fontaine\n|-\n|  [[College soccer|Soccer]]\n| [[High Point Panthers Men's Soccer|Panthers men's soccer]]\n| EJ O'Keeffe\n!\n| [[Track & Field]] ([[Track & Field#Indoor|Indoor]] & [[Track & Field#Outdoor|Outdoor]])\n| \n| Mike Esposito\n|-\n|  [[Track & Field]] ([[Track & Field#Indoor|Indoor]] & [[Track & Field#Outdoor|Outdoor]])\n| \n| Mike Esposito\n!\n| [[Volleyball]]\n| [[High Point Panthers women's volleyball|Panthers women's volleyball]]\n| Ryan Meek\n|}\n;Notes\n{{reflist|group=v}}\n\n=== Men's basketball ===\n{{main|High Point Panthers men's basketball}}\nThe team began varsity play in 1927-28 and was a charter member of the North State Conference (now Conference Carolinas) from 1930-31 through 1996-97, when the school began its transition to NCAA Division I. High Point won 15 regular-season championships and 13 tournament championships while in the North State Conference and participated in the NAIA national tournament in 1939, 1942, 1946, 1951, 1964, 1965, 1969 and 1979. High Point participated in the NCAA Division II Tournament in 1997.\n\nHPU moved up to NCAA Division I in 1999-2000 and joined the [[Big South Conference]]. The Panthers made it to the Big South final in their first year of eligibility in 2002 and also made it to the championship game in 2004. HPU has had two Big South Players of the Year: [[Danny Gathings]] (2003\u201304) and Arizona Reid (2006\u201307, 2007\u201308). Reid is the only player in conference history with over 2,000 points and 1,000 rebounds and was A.P. All-American honorable mention twice. In 2011-12, guard Nick Barbour broke Reid's Division I scoring record, finishing his career with 2,121 points.<ref>The 2,121 points total is derived from the 2,092 career points as cited here: [http://espn.go.com/blog/statsinfo/post/_/id/39192 Wednesday Recap: Hummel turns a corner - Stats & Info Blog - ESPN] plus the 29 total points scored in the two games after playing Campbell, indicated in the game log here: [http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/player/gamelog/_/id/42014/year/2012/nick-barbour Nick Barbour Stats, News, Videos, Highlights, Pictures, Bio - High Point Panthers - ESPN]</ref> Barbour became the second player in team history to lead HPU in scoring four times in a row.<ref name=gamenotes>{{cite web|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/wake/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/2011-12/release/release_20111207aaa_high.pdf|title=High Point University 2011-12 Men's Basketball Game Notes|author=|date=|website=cstv.com}}</ref>\n\nThe team's prominent alumni include current head coach [[Tubby Smith]],<ref name=gamenotes/> former NBA head coach [[Gene Littles]] and former NBA referee Joe Forte. Littles is the program's all-time leading scorer, with 2,398 points from 1965-69.<ref name=gamenotes/> [[George Nostrand]] played at High Point from 1941\u201344 and went on to play in the first NBA game ever in 1946. Along with Cherry, High Point's prominent head coaches have been Virgil Yow (1933\u201345, 1953\u201362), [[J.D. Barnett]] (1971\u201372), [[Jerry Steele]] (1972-2003) and [[Bart Lundy]] (2003\u201309).\n\n=== Women's basketball ===\n{{main|High Point Panthers women's basketball}}\n[[File:Jennifer Hoover Head Coach High Point University.jpg|thumb|Jennifer Hoover, Head Coach, accepting Maggie Dixon Rookie Coach of the Year Award]]\nHigh Point University started women's basketball in 1967-68 and the team is now coached by DeUnna Hendrix (pronounced de-AH-nah), who was hired in May 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://highpointpanthers.com/news/2012/5/18/W-Basketball_0518122128.aspx |title=High Point University Panthers - DeUnna Hendrix named head coach of HPU women's basketball |publisher=Highpointpanthers.com |date=2012-05-18 |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> Hendrix served as assistant coach for one season under [[Jennifer Hoover]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hpe.com/view/full_story/12750280/article-HPU-hires-Hoover# |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-12-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111108092359/http://hpe.com/view/full_story/12750280/article-HPU-hires-Hoover# |archive-date=2011-11-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In Hoover's only season in 2011-12, the team achieved a record of 20\u201313. Her performance earned her the [[Maggie Dixon Award|Maggie Dixon Rookie of the Year award]], presented to a coach with remarkable success in their rookie year as a head coach.<ref name=\"2012 Hoover\"/> Hoover was then hired by her alma mater, Wake Forest, to be head coach in May 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wakeforestsports.com/sports/w-baskbl/spec-rel/050912aaa.html |title=Hall of Famer Jen Hoover Named Wake Forest Head Women's Basketball Coach - The Official Site of Wake Forest Demon Deacon Athletics |publisher=Wakeforestsports.com |date= |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref>\n\nHigh Point won the 1978 AIAW Division II national championship with a 92-88 overtime win over South Carolina State. The following year, High Point set a program record with 33 wins but was unable to defend its national title, falling to Tougaloo in the AIAW Region II Tournament.\n\nHigh Point completed its transition to Division I in 1999-2000 and joined the Big South Conference. High Point has finished above .500 in the Big South in every season since 2000-01. HPU won the Big South regular season championship in 2006-07, the team's only title since joining the league. High Point finished second in the Big South regular season and made it to the Big South tournament final in 2011-12, just the second time the team finished in the top two in the standings and made it to the championship in the same season. High Point earned its second WNIT berth in 2012.\n\nHigh Point\u2019s all-time leading scorer is current Spring Hill College head coach Karen (Curtis) McConico who scored 2,612 points from 1994-98. The team\u2019s most prominent alumnus is former Duke head coach and current television color commentator [[Debbie Leonard]] who played for High Point from 1970-74.<ref>[http://www.theacc.com/legends/wbb/2011/acc-legends-playerpage-Debbie-Leonard.html ]{{dead link|date=September 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe first female player played on a college men's basketball team in 1944 when then High Point men's coach Virgil Yow recruited Nancy Isenhour to be on the team. She started three games.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.journalnow.com/sports/2011/aug/14/wsmet06-yow-coached-championship-teams-with-practi-ar-1297981/ |title=Yow coached championship teams with practice, practice, practice - Winston-Salem Journal: Nation / World |publisher=.journalnow.com |date=2011-08-14 |accessdate=2015-09-21 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130127001803/http://www2.journalnow.com/sports/2011/aug/14/wsmet06-yow-coached-championship-teams-with-practi-ar-1297981/# |archive-date=2013-01-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Cross country and track & field ===\nHead coach Mike Esposito leads HPU's men's and women's cross country, indoor and outdoor track & field teams. Esposito was coach at [[Mount Tabor High School]] in Winston-Salem, North Carolina, for 19 years and has been High Point's head coach since 2005. HPU's longest-tenured coach was Bob Davidson, who led HPU for 39 seasons into the early 2000s. The Panthers' strongest events are cross country and long distance events in track & field. HPU's men's cross country team won three-straight Big South Championships from 2002\u201304 and has been runner-up at the Big South Championship from 2007-11. The women's cross country team won its first Big South Championship in 2011 and Esposito was named conference Coach of the Year. The Panthers have had one NCAA Division I All-American in track & field, Jemissa Hess in the indoor mile in 2005. Two alumni have competed in the Olympics: Taylor Milne represented Canada in the 1,500-meter in 2008 and Tamas Kovacs represented Hungary in the marathon in 2012. Other notable alumni include former Tennessee head coach Bill Webb and current ZAP Fitness runners Jesse Cherry and Cole Atkins. HPU's Vert Stadium is named in honor of Dick Vert, an HPU trustee who was a cross country and middle distance runner and graduated from HPU in 1960.\n\n=== Football ===\nHigh Point University had football from the 1920s until 1950 and was a member of the North State Conference. HPU played at NC State in the 1930 season opener, which was the first night football game played in the state of North Carolina. The team played at Albion Millis Stadium, now the site of Vert Stadium. There is often speculation about High Point restarting a football program but no timeline has been announced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greensborosports.com/2010/09/15/hpu-will-add-football-but-new-arena-for-basketball-and-pharmacy-school-will-come-first-as-part-of-2-1-billion-expansion/ |title=HPU will add football, but new arena for basketball and pharmacy school will come first as part of $2.1 billion expansion |publisher=Greensboro Sports |date=2010-09-15 |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Men's golf ===\nMen's golf is one of High Point's longest-running sports behind men's basketball. The team moved up to NCAA Division I in 1999 and had its best Big South Championship finish, third, in 2006. HPU's highest individual finisher was Ryan Taylor, who placed second in 2007. The team's most prominent alumnus is Roger Watson, who played for HPU from 1963\u201366, won national club championships in 1974 and 1975 and has since been inducted to several halls of fame, including the NAIA Hall of Fame and North Carolina Sports Hall of Fame.<ref>[http://www.ncshof.org/inductees_detail.php?i_recid=286 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101220133934/http://www.ncshof.org/inductees_detail.php?i_recid=286 |date=December 20, 2010 }}</ref> High Point named Brady Gregor head coach in 2016, replacing Greg Flesher (2012\u201316).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://highpointpanthers.com/news/2012/5/25/M-Golf_0525124932.aspx |title=High Point University Panthers - Flesher named head coach of HPU men's golf |publisher=Highpointpanthers.com |date=2012-05-25 |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Women's golf ===\nHigh Point University started women's golf in 2003-04 and the team achieved its highest Big South Championship finish - third - in 2005. HPU has had one individual Big South women's golf champion, Ann Marie Dalton in 2008. Vici Pate Flesher was named head coach in 2010 and led HPU to a fourth-place finish in the 2011 Big South Championship, up from eighth the year before.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://highpointpanthers.com/news/2011/4/13/W-Golf_0413110630.aspx |title=High Point University Panthers - HPU women's golf takes fourth at Big South Championship |publisher=Highpointpanthers.com |date=2011-04-13 |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> Pate Flesher led the [[Methodist University|Methodist College]] women's golf team to seven-straight NCAA Division III championships.\n\n=== Men's lacrosse ===\nHigh Point University announced the addition of men's [[lacrosse]] as part of the university's $2.1 billion growth plan in September 2010. HPU's first varsity men's lacrosse season will be 2013. HPU named Jon Torpey head coach in 2010 and he joined HPU on a full-time basis in June 2011. Torpey's college teammate at Ohio State, Pat Tracy, as well as former Maryland attacker Michael Phipps joined HPU as assistant coaches in 2011. High Point brought in 20 players for the 2011-12 season, who redshirted in preparation for the inaugural varsity season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://highpointpanthers.com/news/2011/8/30/M-Lacrosse_0830111112.aspx |title=High Point University Panthers - High Point men's lacrosse begins individual workouts |publisher=Highpointpanthers.com |date=2011-08-30 |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> The 2012-13 roster features 39 players, including three from North Carolina and three from Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://highpointpanthers.com/roster.aspx?tab=roster2&path=mlacrosse |title=High Point University Panthers - 2016 Men's Lacrosse Roster |publisher=Highpointpanthers.com |date= |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Women's lacrosse ===\n{{main|High Point Panthers women's lacrosse}}\nHigh Point University announced the addition of women's lacrosse in 2009 and won the National Lacrosse Conference championship in its first season of 2011. The Panthers went 15-4 in their inaugural campaign, setting a record for wins by a first-year NCAA Division I program. The previous record was 13-4 by Navy in 2008. The team is coached by Lyndsey Boswell, who was named NLC Coach of the Year in 2011. She had been head coach at St. Andrews Presbyterian College and was an NCAA Division II All-American while playing at Pfeiffer. HPU attacker Grace Gaeng transferred from Maryland and was named NLC Player of the Year in 2011. The team repeated with a 15-4 record in 2012 and won the NLC regular season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://highpointpanthers.com/schedule.aspx?schedule=308&path=wlax |title=High Point University Panthers - 2011-12 Women's Lacrosse Schedule |publisher=Highpointpanthers.com |date= |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> High Point moved to the Big South Conference in 2013 and has won the conference tournament in 2013, 2014, and 2017. In the 2013 NCAA tournament, they lost 18-7 to [[Loyola Greyhounds|Loyola (Maryland)]] and in 2014 they fell 18-4 to [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish|Notre Dame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highpointpanthers.com/documents/2017/3/20/2017_WLAX_Record_Book.pdf|title=High Point University Panthers - 2017 Women's Lacrosse Record Book|author=|date=|website=www.highpointpanthers.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Men's soccer ===\n{{main|High Point Panthers Men's Soccer}}\nHigh Point men's soccer began play in 1929. In their second season in 1930, the Panthers hosted the first-ever intercollegiate soccer game held below the Mason\u2013Dixon line, beating Catawba College 1-0.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://issuu.com/hpenterprise/docs/everythinghp-reduce/75 |title=Everything High Point 2011 by High Point Enterprise |publisher=ISSUU |date= |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> The team was dropped in 1942 due to World War II but was then brought back in 1971 and moved to Division I in 1999.\n\nHPU recorded its best overall record and won its first-ever Big South Regular Season Championship in 2010 when the team went 16-4-1 overall and perfect 8-0-0 in the Big South. The Panthers reached the Big South Championship twice but lost both times, falling to Winthrop in 2006 and Coastal Carolina in 2010. Karo Okiomah became HPU\u2019s first Big South Player of the Year and All-American after scoring 12 goals in 16 games for the Panthers in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.socceramerica.com/article/40731/mens-ncaa-division-i-all-american-team.html |title=Men's NCAA Division I All-American Team 12/11/2010 |publisher=SoccerAmerica |date=2010-12-11 |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> The team achieved national rankings in 2010 and 2012 and is the only HPU team to achieve a Div. I ranking to date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://highpointpanthers.com/news/2012/9/17/M-Soccer_0917123342.aspx?path=msoc |title=High Point University Panthers - Men's soccer ranked 28th by College Soccer News |publisher=Highpointpanthers.com |date= |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> Dustin Fonder was named High Point's head coach in 2007 and was named Big South Coach of the Year in 2009 and 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigsouthsports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=25877&SPID=2024&DB_LANG=C&DB_OEM_ID=4800&ATCLID=205028238 |title=Big South Announces 2010 Men's Soccer Awards |publisher=BigSouthSports.com |date=2010-11-11 |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Women's soccer ===\n{{main|High Point Panthers women's soccer}}\nHigh Point University began women's soccer in 1992 and won Big South Tournaments in 2003, 2007, 2009 and 2010, advancing to the NCAA Tournament each of those seasons. The program holds a Big South record with six-straight shutouts in conference tournament games, not allowing a goal in either the 2009 or 2010 tournaments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigsouthsports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=25860&SPID=2022&DB_LANG=C&DB_OEM_ID=4800&ATCLID=205026569 |title=High Point Wins Big South Women's Soccer Championship |publisher=BigSouthSports.com |date=2010-11-08 |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> HPU tied for its first Big South regular season title in 2010. In its most recent NCAA Tournament game at Maryland on November 12, 2010, High Point led 1\u20130 before falling to the Terrapins, 4\u20131. The team is coached by former Francis Marion head coach Marty Beall.\n\n=== Women's volleyball ===\n{{main|High Point Panthers women's volleyball}}\nHigh Point University began its volleyball program in 1973 and moved up to NCAA Division I in 1999. The Panthers tied for their first Big South regular season championship in 2008, going 26-7 overall and 13-3 in league play. Former Dayton and Maryland assistant coach Jason Oliver was named HPU's head coach in 2009 and led the team to its first-ever Big South Tournament title and NCAA appearance in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://highpointpanthers.com/news/2010/11/20/Volleyball_1120103742.aspx?path=wvball |title=High Point University Panthers - High Point wins first-ever Big South volleyball title |publisher=Highpointpanthers.com |date=2010-11-20 |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> Audie Gonzalez was named tournament MVP. The Panthers played No. 12 Duke, taking a 3-0 loss at Cameron Indoor Stadium in their first NCAA Tournament game on December 3, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://highpointpanthers.com/news/2010/12/3/Volleyball_1203103005.aspx?path=wvball |title=High Point University Panthers - Panthers fall to No. 12 Duke in opening round of NCAA Tourney |publisher=Highpointpanthers.com |date=2010-12-03 |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> In 2016, Tom Mendoza was named head coach, and in his first year, he led High Point to a 23-10 record and another Big South conference title. In the [[2016 NCAA Division I Women's Volleyball Tournament|NCAA tournament]], the Panthers lost to No. 7 North Carolina in three sets.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highpointpanthers.com/news/2016/12/2/volleyball-hpus-postseason-run-ends-in-3-0-setback-at-unc.aspx|title=HPU\u2019s postseason run ends in 3-0 setback at UNC|author=|date=|website=High Point University}}</ref>\n\n=== Men's and Women's Tennis ===\nHigh Point University stopped its tennis program in 2008. Most recently the 2003 Men's team won the Big South Tennis Championship defeating fellow Big South member Winthrop University. The Panthers, who played in five consecutive NAIA national championship tournaments (1970\u201375) finished #4 in 1974 NAIA Men's National Championship in Kansas City, Mo. Coach Ray Alley was named 1975 NAIA men's Tennis National Coach of the Year. Peter Ranney was named NAIA Honorable Mention All-American in 1975.\n\nFinland stars from the early 1990s and 2000s included All-Conference, Rolex Champion, and Athletes of the Year players Vesa Kemppainen, Pekka Pohjamo, and Tavvi Surousa.  High Point star Pekka Pohjamo won the singles and doubles at the 1994 Rolex ITA Collegiate Invitational. He teamed with American Donald Marriott to take the doubles title. Donald Marriott who played in the early 1990s also garnered All-Conference, Millis-Scholar Athlete, and All-District awards. Marriott would also win multiple \"City of High Point\" tennis championships 96,98,03 and North Carolina State Doubles titles including the 2003 NC State Mixed Doubles Championship. He is currently the Men's and Women's Head Tennis coach for Lee's McRae College in Banner Elk, NC.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"2012 Hoover\">{{cite web|title=Jennifer Hoover named the 2012 Spalding Maggie Dixon Division I Rookie Coach of the Year|url=http://www.wbca.org/blog/index.cfm/2012/4/2/Jennifer-Hoover-named-2012-Spalding-Maggie-Dixon-NCAA-DI-Rookie-Coach-of-the-Year/|publisher=WBCA|accessdate=6 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120411123354/http://www.wbca.org/blog/index.cfm/2012/4/2/Jennifer-Hoover-named-2012-Spalding-Maggie-Dixon-NCAA-DI-Rookie-Coach-of-the-Year/#|archive-date=2012-04-11|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.highpointpanthers.com/}}\n\n{{Big South Conference navbox}}\n{{North Carolina Sports}}\n\n[[Category:High Point Panthers| ]]\n", "name_user": "Golfbuddy22", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/High_Point_Panthers"}
